\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid13179849 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2384896\charrsid15017164 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Could you say your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 My name is Verney - Verney, of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}77 Colne Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, Brightlingsea. I am seventy-two years of age and was originally born in the Borough of Woolwich.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You said you were seventy-two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 I'm seventy - 1899. '99, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What year were you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 I was married in 1939. Just a few months before war
 broke out. Rather late because I had been - in the Army for years and abroad for a long while too. So that - one - well - didn't get entangled as a matter - no, I - as I say was born in Woolwich and lived all my life right up to 1915 in Woolwich. In - le
t
 me see - one two, three, four houses, all within a matter of - a quarter of a mile of each other. All within a radius of quarter of a mile. That was - well it was in the parish of Plumstead. But in that the portion of parish of Plumstead which was on the
 
border of the parish of - of the - of the parish of Woolwich. On the top of a hill which overlooked the barracks, and - Woolwich Arsenal. My father was employed in Woolwich Arsenal, he was a - a - he originally came from Hampshire, the same as my mother. 
T
hey were country people originally, although in their young days both of them left the village, my mother went into service in Margate and other places, Margate mostly. And my father - well he was employed on farms and then - when he was about sixteen I t
h
ink went over to Aldershot and joined the Army. His father found it out and claimed him out and he was dragged back to the farm - to the farms. But at about eighteen he left again and joined the Army and he then continued until - oh - about in the 1890's,
 
when he came - he served then in - Ireland, Jersey, India, and various other places. The consequence of that of course, practically everybody we knew, and of course Woolwich being a garrison town, practically everybody we knew were military people. And be
i
ng - close to the barracks, overlooking the barracks actually, I suppose for a great deal of time I spent quite a lot of my time in the barracks. As a mater of fact, the meals that I had as a schoolboy in - in the barrack room with the troops was - well I
 can't - I can't count them, I was always up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Was your father an engineer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No. My father was just an ordinary - ordinary labourer. He was - he first, when he left the Army became a - was - got a job on the London North Eastern railway. But he wasn't in that long before -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What was he doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Just ordinary labouring. And then he got a job in - Woolwich Arsenal - as a labourer where he was then until - he was found redundant in the - 1950's, just after - just after the - after 
the - the last war. He - although he had about twelve years in the Army, he never fired a shot in anger, he never saw any wars or anything. He - he - wasn't called - he was on reserve when the Boer War broke out. But he wasn't called up for it because he 
h
ad broken his trigger finer, and consequently he couldn't bend it and of course in those days they hadn't - realised that you could pull a trigger with another finger. So he was never called up. But it was just - just before the Boer War that he - he got 
the job in the Arsenal and of course he worked then right through the first world war and the second world war there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So in 1911 he was a labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes. Oh yes. As regards childhood well, there were only three of us in the - the family beside my mother and father. Sorry. Yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your mother was a domestic servant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 My mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 That was the only job she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 That was the only job she had, well various jobs is domestic service, the last 
one I think was in - Margate. Where she was a domestic servant in a family who I believe were Jews. But - whether they were or not I don't know, not that it matters very much, but she was there for - oh, some years. Of course she and my father came from t
h
e same village, they knew each other as children. And strange to say, my father - and his sister married my mother - or at least, my father married my mother of course, and her brother married my father's sister, and we both lived in the same street, so w
e
 were an awful crossed family. But that's the not the only main wangle we had. I had another uncle - well no, two aunts. One married a man and the other one married his nephew. So we got further complicated 'cos I never did try to sort out exactly - where
 
we - exact relation - ships were really. But - that was just how things happened in - the country villages of those days. Of course most - my - holidays for instance were spent in the village. We never went anywhere - except to the village. And - of cours
e
 I do - sort of can remember - what village life was like before 1914. Yes. Mother - was - in - domestic service and - I don't mind telling you it gave her a jolly good - training for - housekeeping because - although we'd never got - there wasn't much mo
ney coming into the house - we were never without a meal, and a jolly god meal at that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 She didn't take in any work or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. Well - occasionally she did, once or twice. She used - did have a spasm, I don't know why it was - but she did t
ake in making soldiers shirts. And the remuneration was absolutely - putrid and she didn't carry it on very long. And then she also had another spasm, I think it was more by sort of talking to neighbours, she did have another spasm of sewing - the covers 
o
n tennis balls. But - she could never get on with that and - she never did that very long. But again that was - a - a very small remuneration, you - had to do a dozen I think before you got about sixpence. And - to stitch covers on a - on a tennis ball is
 
not a particularly easy job, because you can't turn the thing inside out to stitch. As regards the shirts, well they were the ordinary - the coarse flannel shirts the Army used to wear in those days and they were pretty heavy going. But she never did any 
outside work other than those two odd - two or three odd occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have to help at all with work with the shirts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No, no. She did that because - as a matter of fact I wasn't so very old then and of course my sisters, who were youn
ger than me, were really - might as well call babies at the time you see. Oh no, we didn't, she - just used to do them at odd times. Perhaps she'd do a dozen in a - in a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 She wouldn't take them to the factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No, no, she always took
 those because you had to go down in the daytime and of course I was at school. There was not a great deal of - outwork of that sort done amongst - any of our neighbours or friends. There were people in the street that used to do - sewing for - local tail
ors sort of outwork. Another friend of ours used to do work making whips - plaiting whips. Which - I don't suppose is done nowadays. They used to - the husband and wife - practically kept them - well, they - their only occupation. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 And they'd - be - have lon
g strips of leather cut very, very finely about - well it depended on what kind of whip they were making, but it usually used to be from about a quarter of an inch wide at one end, then there was a sort of a long triangle and the other end'd be practicall
y - hairsbreadth. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
And then they - usually - they used to use about - six or seven of these strips and they'd be tied onto a hook on the doorpost and then they get across the other side of the room and they'd be - twiddling about, plaiting those in the most 
fantastic patterns. Four hours. And they'd do quite a number of those, and kept quite a lot of the saddlers shops and the - the horse people about in the district with whips, which was then of course an old - - one of the old - home - they were old countr
y people as well, but I can't tell you where they came from.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You knew them quite well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
I knew them quite well, oh yes, they used to live - I often used to sit in their kitchen and watch them - fascinated - making these whips, and then used to be
 fascinated to see the - lovely pattern they made and the closeness of the work and then they all had to be pipeclayed after they'd all - plaited them. Rubbed over with white clay - white pipeclay to make them nice and white. And they didn't stop white ve
r
y long after of course they got in use. But they had to be nice and white for the shop you see. Then they had to be mounted on these long things and - it was quite a - well I suppose it's - I've never heard of anybody making whips nowadays. No. Although t
h
is was in London by the way. But of course there were - numbers of horsemen about in London. And everybody had their horse and cart, and the tradesmen and that sort of thing. But - mother - mother and father never did anything of that. I never had to do a
ny sort of help to the house, although I did have little jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you tell me what those little jobs were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, yes - I often laugh about it now when I see the boys nowadays, I did paper round - newspaper round. I used to have to be up at six i
n the morning. And go on a newspaper round which extended from - well, practically here in Colne Road up to All Saints Church on the top of the hill, that's a mike and a quarter away. All uphill. And various side streets off it. I used to go out with a bi
g
 bag full of newspapers and there - then there were more newspapers than there are nowadays. Not only newspapers but magazines and periodicals and sometimes it was as much as I could do to stand upright with the bag hanging over my shoulder. I used to hav
e
 to deliver all those in the mornings and then get back home to have breakfast and get to school. That was every morning of the week, Sunday mornings I used to have to do the same thing, and - that was a bit heavier sometimes because - Sunday newspapers u
s
ed to be a bit thicker and there was quite a number of them. And then after I got home and had breakfast I had to go out and call at every house and collect the money. So consequently I was really up to about one o'clock on a Sunday morning doing that job
. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 And I used to come home with a - weighted down with pockets full of coppers - pennies or - silver etcetera. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Then I had to check it all through with my book in the shop. And for that I used to get the princely sum of - I think it was three and sixpence. Bu
t - it doesn't seem to have done me any good although I don't mind telling you I used to hate it at times. Especially in the winter, having to get up in the dark and go out in the cold and frosty morning. And many's the time mother come out with me and he
lped, you know. But - I had that for some - some time, and then afterwards I gave that up, and I suppose when I was about - twelve or thirteen, I got a job in the - corner grocers shop which was grocers off }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 license}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of delivery and keeping the shelves in the shop - full and - crating up the empty bottles and all this sort of thing. That was after -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 That was after you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no, this was while was at school. Oh yes, all - all while I was at school. I left school - when I was fourteen, that
 was in 1913. And - a week after I left school I started a job as an office boy. Which I had to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 then from - half past eight in the morning - 'til half past six at night, except on Thursdays, when, being in a shop, the shop shut on Thursdays, early closing day, but on Friday }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 nights}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 we always had to work an hour later and on Saturdays on 'til somewhere about ten o'clock at night. Then my - my original salary was seven and sixpence a week. After I'd been there a year - I got ten shillings a week, and I th
ought I was a millionaire. But - I carried on that job until - January 1915. When we had a clerk in the office who was of partly German parentage, and of course this was after the outbreak of the 1914 war, and this man would insist on speaking German offi
c
e and sometimes - speaking to me in German and one - he was always annoying me, and one day he annoyed me so much, I was sitting on the other side of a - sloping desk you know, on a big office stool, and he annoyed me so much that I picked up a ledger and
 
threw it at him I missed him it's true but - through that misconduct I got the sack. Well - I was rather horrified, I didn't go home and tell them I got the sack at home, but I finished up the week, got a weeks notice. Got my pay and - handed over the nec
e
ssary at home. Never said a word but I made up my mind that - well I'd have to get another job quick and - on the Monday morning - on the Saturday morning I went out as if I was going to work - instead of that went to the - the recruiting office. And - af
t
er walking round it about four times I summed up enough courage to - get to the doorway and then bumped into an enormous great recruiting sergeant who wanted to know what I wanted, so I said I wanted to join the Army. He said, how old are you? I said, eig
h
teen. He said, look old boy, go and have a walk round and make sure how old you are and come back. So I did, and came back and - I said I was eighteen and a half. So he marched me inside, and sat down and filled up a long form. Then marched me into - oh, 
s
aid go in there and get undressed and I opened the door and went in there and there was a whole crowd of about twenty men in there, all old enough - some of them old enough to be my father, all stark naked and I had to do the same - which was frightfully 
e
mbarrassing I can assure you. But - anyway from there we marched into a - into a real old - fogey of a doctor. I don't know when he - passed his medicals but it must have been - about the Crimean I think, but he looked at the papers, gave a huh, and I was
 
passed. Whether he thought I was eighteen and a half I don't know. Any rate, from there I marched into another dear old gent, a Major who administers the oath, I took the oath, was presented with a shilling, the famous Queen's shilling, which I don't mind
 
telling you I never kept, I spent. And two and six - ration money until - to last me until Monday, and a railway warrant to proceed to Aldershot, to proceed there on the Monday. Well I went home and - I then broke the news. Of course there was much - grum
b
ling from mother but father said, oh let him go, it'll do him good. - And so that's how I joined the Army. Within six months I was in Egypt. Three months later than that I was flat on me back nearly dead, from typhoid fever. But I didn't come out of the A
rmy until - I was in South Africa in 1919. When - it was a case of my seven years service, I joined as a regular soldier, my seven years service expired and it was a case }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  either coming back to England - where things weren't too good - or signing on again
. At the time I had an offer of - the - joining the South African Airforce and the pay was very much better than a soldier's pay, Imperial Soldier's pay, and so I elected to join the South African Airforce, so I left the - British army one day and joined 
t
he South African - the South African Air force the next day. And so I had no really broken service, and I remained with them - until I was invalided out in 19 - 25 I think it was. Then I - well I went farming in South Africa for - somewhere about nine mon
ths and -
