No, I went to - some very distant relatives - who had a farm. I went down there really to - recuperate from this nervous breakdown and - oh I stayed there until they sold the farm up. At least I helped t
o sell it up. I used to do the - selling of the produce etcetera to - the local - Indian merchants. The local - native store. But - after that I went down to Durban and - well I was out of work for - wasn't doing anything for a little while. And then I go
t
 a job on the South African railway, so I still became a government serviceman - servant and I remained there until - 1928. There I was in the - I was in the stationmasters office. I was in charge of - gangs of - native workers, mostly Indian. And - it wa
s at the time of course there was a great - political upheaval then, apartheid was really starting. But - we won't go into that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 When you were in the Army were you doing clerical work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 I was doing clerical work the whole time. I was - first - it 
was really funny, my - I was doing ordinary clerical work in England when I went out to Egypt I was popped in to a - a mechanical transport store, and I was in charge of the - of the spare parts store. At five different makes of lorries and quite frankly 
I
 didn't know the back of a car from another - from the front end. And - people - men used to come and - present me with - requisitions for spare parts and I used to have to dodge behind the partition, grab the catalogue of - the particular make and turn u
p 'til I found a picture of what the thing was they wanted. But luckily I never got found out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 I - I - carried on that - oh for a long, long while. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Until I went - I was taken sick. Then when I went out to - from there I went out to - Greece. I was again the
 mechanical transport but - I had nothing to do with the transport, I was then - orderly room clerk, I was in charge of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 orderly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  room. Doing general jobs. And from there I went to - general headquarters where I was politely given the job of - of compili
ng statistics for the feeding of the whole Army in Greece and various other parts of the Near East. Gathering in statistics from all the various supply depots, the quantities of each particular food they had and then having to work it out at so much a - p
e
r man per day as to how many days food there was in reserve and if there wasn't - the - correct number then having to compile a 1 cablegram to the War Office in London calling for more supplies, which used to cause some great fun at times, especially when
 
we found that we had five million pounds worth of dried beans which we didn't want and - we cabled to the War Office telling them of this and asking them if they wanted them, which they replied sending us another five million pounds. We cabled back again 
s
aying we didn't want them and dash me if they didn't cable again and send us another five million. So that the - luckily we were at that time feeding refugees from - the revolution in Russia - so that we were able to get rid of the wretched things by feed
ing the refugees on them, much to their annoyance. But - that's rather rushing things a bit..
