\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would she take in a soldier or someone like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Yes. Sometimes - or perhaps - possibly - the wife of a soldier who wasn't - entitled to married quarters. You see, sometimes it would be that, we'd - who' she'd take in. But nobody - never made a real business of it like some people did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did she ever have anyone to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. Oh no. Except if she was queer or anything of that sort. Then - well my aunt would - my father's sister from up the roa
d would come in you see. Oh no - mother was always very independent like that. Neighbours were always kept outside the front door. She didn't want them coming in - poking their nose round. The neighbours used to come in of course but - not very often. If 
t
hey did come in it was usually a sort of - state occasion when they were taken into the front room and - tea was served on the best china and that sort of thing you see, a state occasion. But as for the sort of - as you get in some places - popping in nex
t
 door and having a chat, oh no. Although she was always ready to talk over the back fence or over the front gate - the front - front door. But always kept a certain amount of - aloofness from them. She never - never did mix much with - with the neighbours
.
 For instance, on one side of us we had - a Roman Catholic family, now I hope you're not a Roman Catholic - and - of course they were - always beyond the pale. On the other side of us we had a family who were rather - happy go lucky, they were a very big 
f
amily. The father - was working in the Arsenal, he was very much better position than my father, he was a foreman, but he was a big club man, political club man, he was a big Radical, Election days he'd always be walking about with a very large red rosett
e
. But - they never had sort of tuppence to bless themselves with, that family. And - although mother would talk to them she was always - rather looked down her nose at them. And - the same with quite a lot of other people in the - in the street you see, t
hey were that sort of - what shall I say - sort of social barriers really, people put up themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Why do you think she thought she was superior like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh I don't think she felt she was superior, but - she couldn't abide title-tattle and - 
gossip - and she wasn't going to have everybody - gossiping about her around the street you know, around the town sort of thing. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 She didn't need help from neighbours ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No. Oh - well she'd always got - my aunt up the road. And - 
they were both - both my father and mother were very healthy, it was only one occasion I can remember my mother being very ill, or twice - two occasions. But on those, well my sisters were able to do things in the house you see, and my aunt - under the su
pervision of my aunt, so that there was no - no need for - help or anything of that sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have to help in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes, I was supposed to do all sorts of jobs, used to try - try and get out of them. Such as I only mentioned the 
other night of - cleaning the knives on the old - board with a piece of lino nailed on it and - sprinkling }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 ofOakley's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 powder - knife powder over them and rubbing the knives up and down. Usually that used to be a Saturday job. Sometimes I'd get the job of -
 chopping some wood. But - we weren't expected to do a lot in the house really. Oh, and pushing my sisters, yes, get little jobs like that. But - even that was not very often. Because as I say, I used to object to it so strongly that - I think mother gave
 
it up eventually. I used to have to do messages. Go up to the shop and get this and that and the other. And always - went out with my mother shopping because she was deaf. On one side. Well at least she was - she was practically totally deaf. And - of cou
r
se if she was in a shop, a noisy shop, she couldn't hear what was said to her. And so we always used to have to go out with her - and - sort of act as interpreter really. That was about the only jobs I ever used to get really at home. We - clean shoes som
etimes. Mostly father used to do those Sunday mornings but - sometimes I used to get roped in to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What else did he do besides cleaning shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, he did the very little in the house. He used to look after the garden. He was - of course being a countryman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164  always}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 wanted to do - have a garden, and mother was the same as far as that goes. He used to - sometimes - for one period we did - keep chicken at the bottom of the garden. Which - of course, provided eggs and also - provided chicken f
or the pot. He used to grow quite a lot of vegetables in the garden. And - at one - well, during the first world war he did quite a bit of business on his own of - providing the local butcher with - rabbits. He had rabbits in the house. He only had one or
 
two which - we used to have for the pot. And - oh we bred and he managed to get - oh, quite a good - good supply. The local butcher found it out and offered him a good price for them so father used to keep the - local butcher supplied with rabbits now and
 again. But - that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 merely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 a sort of - well, bit of pocket money job really. Although father would very often hand it over. But you see father was one of those - he was rather - what shall I say, happy-go-lucky - he didn't care what happened. Hail, rain 
or shine; as long as he - could have his pipe and his - and his pint of - beer at night. He didn't mind what - what we did. Or at least what happened I should say, he did mind what we did. I used to have to - very often go down to the tobacconist and get 
his tobacco for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have to fetch beer for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No, no. No. He }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 always}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  went out for that. Always went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 out,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 unless there were any relatives staying with us - when - they - or some friends of his, one or two people used to come in, they
 used to have a - an evening playing crib, when there was always - he'd always go out and fetch the job of beer, it was only across the road. But - that didn't happen very often because mother used to object. And - I don't mind telling you we all objected
 
because you could never use the room for three or four days afterwards, he used to - smell like at - well, everybody smoking you - used to go in the room when they were playing cards and you could see across it. But - that was only natural. No, father - w
e
 managed quite well on what - father earned really. I know that sounds rather strange for those days and - the rates of pay and that but we did, mother was a very good manager, she was the manager of the house. I'm afraid the whole family was rather a - a
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 matriarchic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 family. Mother - mother ruled the roost, put it that way. But - we got on quite well and - as I say, I can never remember even - well, things were a bit tight, we were never without a jolly good meal. In the winter there was always - a large - 
pot of - soup on the hob, always. I can always - often remember going over to the local butcher for - three penn'orth or two penn'orth of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 bones}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 , which were always brought home and put into the - stockpot. And - well they - even on Fridays when perhaps mone
y then run out, we always had a meal of some sort of other. A real country style, yes. Everything - it was mostly based on a country style of - of living. Occasionally we'd get something sent up from the country, but very seldom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What would you get sent up?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 A rabbit or something of that sort. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 Very, very seldom though. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 We only went down there once a year. And then it was a major operation. Because it meant writing round to all sorts of relatives, who could put this one up and who could put that 
one up, and we used to get down to the village - and perhaps father - find mother staying in one house, I'd be staying in another house, my sisters - one sister in another house and the other sister in another house. Just depended who got - who'd got room
. And then of course to get here - it meant - meant case of going up to London of course, getting across to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 Paddington}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, this was from South East London up to - Paddington, and then down, and of course - to get to the village - well - we always had to arrang
e - the station we went to on the railway always had to be arranged according to - my grandfather's programme, because he always collected us in the trap. You see, he was - he was a sweep and did a - a big - connection with all the big country houses roun
d
 about, and - we always - it used to take weeks of arrangement, as to - where we should go, whether we should go to Newbury or to Aldermaston or to Mitcham or to Thatcham. Because just depended which - day he'd be at which house - and so on, and what time
.
 But - we used to go down there and then - he would - mother perhaps would stay with her mother. I'd stay with an uncle, and as I say, we were scattered all over the village. And at that time, I think - the greater part of the village were related to me. 
I
t wasn't a very big village and - there was a - the family goes back in the village for - well at least I've traced them back to the seventeen hundreds. And - the offshoots of the family I don't think there were many people that weren't related to me and 
o
f course - that was the trouble, you could never move in the village without somebody knew and it was always known what I was doing because - as I say, everybody knew me. But we always lived a country life then, thoroughly. Do - doing exactly the same as 
our cousins and - and uncles and aunts, going out collecting wood for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 woodshed - gleaning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 - driving cows home, perhaps one of my uncles was a cowman, I used to go up and - perhaps help him drive the cattle home and - sometimes turn the - the handle of t
he separating machine in the dairy. I used to like doing that because they always used to say, well have a drink of milk, and I always used to put the - the beaker under the wrong spout so I always had a drink of cr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 am. But - we always did - we always did 
things like - like that and - I had relatives living in Newbury and - we'd occasionally go over there, well that of course meant going over in the carrier's cart. Which meant starting about - nine o'clock in the - oh - no - eight o'clock in the morning, a
n
d getting into Newbury somewhere about lunchtime, because we visited all the - the farms and isolated cottages for miles around on either side of the road and - every time you came to a hill you'd very often have to get out and - walk up. And - and that s
ort of thing. And then come home - well, you sat amongst all the - all the produce and - bundles of - reels of barbed wire, bundles of wire netting, sacks of lime, sacks of anything. Oh - all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 bundled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  in the cart together and they all had to be delivered all
 the way round, you'd get home somewhere in dark. Somewhere about eight or nine o'clock at night, having left there about three and it was only seven miles. But - it used to be great fun and we used to - think it was a great - thing.
