\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You went most years did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 We went most years, sometimes we'd miss a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 How long would you go for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well we'd usually go for a fortnight. Sometimes longer. It just depended how long - the family could - put up with us and put us up sort of thing. But - it was of the days of course when - one had to - observe the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 niceties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 as regards the local inhabitants, such as - if you saw the vicar well you always had to - the ladies had to bob to him and the - men had to - either lift their hats or - pull - pull th
eir forelocks, if they didn't he jolly well yelled across the road and told you off. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would that be different from London to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. It was entirely different of course. I mean the - one of the cottages I used to stay in was - with som
e cousins of mine - was a thatched cottage, with a thatched roof. And lie in bed and hear - mice and birds running about in the thatch and - we were just under - underneath the thatch without any - sort of ceiling. The walls of that one were made of chalk
 
cob. It was a very old - very old cottage. And of course - there was no - sanitation. It was the wee house down the - bottom of the garden. And I can always remember one because it had a family seat in it, which - might surprise you, we had a large hole a
n
d a small hole side by side. I know - my mother and sisters used to be terrified of going there because - spiders and all sorts of things used to run all over you while you were there. And - it was also in the woodshed, so you had to go in there regardles
s
 of who was there or whether it was being used, to get some wood for the fire. And - of course water had to be carried - had to come out of the well, there was no laid on water. It was a case of going - well many times I've wound up the - the bucket out o
f
 the well and it - used to want some hauling up. Only to find when you got the bucket up there were a couple of frogs or a newt in it and - but of course you'd have to dish those out and carry the water indoors. It was perfectly - perfectly primitive life
 really and everything was - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7673867\charrsid15017164 horse drawn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 of course, there was no - there were no cars and that sort of thing, I can remember when the carrier turned over to a motor vehicle. It was considered absolutely shocking, but - now of course it's on a main bus route.
