f wild flowers for instance, and we used to go out for - hours scouring the - the downs all over the place for - all the wild flowers of different kinds that we could find and - you'd get an armful of them. Now you can't find them I mean - thirty or forty
 
different - species you'd find. On the chalk, yes, of course you'd get wild scabius and all that sort of thing. Then of course we always used to go - if it was in the autumn we went down there'd be nutting, used to go up the lane nutting and - and - black
berrying, and all those things, and of course all the - all my uncles and aunts did the same. For - for the - cupboard of course, running down into preserves you see. Well for us it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 
romantic,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  I mean, I used to go out with my great-grandmother and - when
 I - I'm talking now of being as a schoolboy, I had - one, two - three - four - five - I had six grandparents living, including great-grandparents. One of them was a dear old lady - she was great on simples and herbs, and I used to have to go out with her
 
herbing. And used to get dosed with the beastly stuff afterwards too. And I - she lived in Newbury and I can remember having - going out with her, if I was staying with her, going out with her on Saturday - shopping, and it was always walking into - littl
