le there it was six or something of sort we were told, well you jolly well deserved it. Got no sympathy at all. In fact - quite possibly you got a - a clout on the side of the head as well, to - just to add to it. And - of course, as regards police, well 
-
 you didn't - regard the policeman as they do today. And the policeman caught you doing something he'd possibly give you a clout, and tell you not to do it again and you - sort of - well you didn't, and the next time you saw him coming you'd run like mad,
 but not because you were frightened of him, because you didn't want another clout.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your parents didn't say they'd call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes, they used to say that. Which was - very often it was a sort of commonplace, rather it took the place of 
the - sort of remark - send for Napoleon, sort of bogey man. I've heard - yes, the bogeyman but - when we were very little perhaps we'd get told if we didn't go to sleep the bogeyman'd come. Or - if you were sleepy, the sandman would come. But there were 
n
o really - sort of threats held out to - to one at all. Except you were sometimes threatened with a - with a clout or something of that sort. But it didn't come off. I can't remember my father chastising me at all. He'd sometimes would threaten to - take 
his belt off. But - -it never came to actually taking it off, thank goodness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So you were never physically punished at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No. No. I can't - except for school. And then not very often. The last time I think the schoolmaster chased me roun
d the hall to catch me, because I objected. Oh no, I don't think - I don't think many children - not in our walk of life, I don't think were - were chastised very much. Of course in some families I agree with you, you might have got - the father was perha
ps a bit - brutal. But - I don't think there were - I don't - I can't recollect any - anybody I know getting sort of thumping good hiding sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Do you feel your mother could show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes. She was - she was very affectio
nate. She - well sort of bestowed more of her affection I suppose on my youngest sister, more than she did on me or my older sister. She was the - my youngest was the sort of baby - well was the baby of the family and of course - was my mother's pet, she 
couldn't do any wrong. But - myself and my oldest sister, we'd often get groused at. And - get chased }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 after}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 - even after I'd married my mother would often tell me, look at me and say,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 hm,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 you don't seem to have washed yourself today - didn't she? Often used 
to say that. And - not privately but in public. She was very - very abrupt. But - she was quite affectionate, she - did everything she possibly could. In fact, I might as well say she was rather - she'd have fought like a tiger for us really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well, he was quite all right, yes, he was quite affectionate, but he was quite all right, he didn't worry himself too much about the family. As long as things were going all right - there was a meal on the table, a roof over his head
 and that sort of thing, he was quite happy. He was - very - happy-go-lucky. Mind you, he would be a bit miserable perhaps we hadn't got a lot in his pocket but - it - it didn't last long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What sort of people do you feel that they hoped their children would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh they all wanted us - myself for instance, they all wanted me to be a white collar person. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Both your father and your mother wanted that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes, and - my sisters, well - the same thing practically, b
ecause my eldest sister - she was a - secretary. And my youngest sister was a court dressmaker. Oh yes, they all wanted us to be - to be up, and there was all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They were ambitious for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. And there was always a certain amount of rivalry - between - her and her brother, who lived in the same }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 road}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, who had - two sons and a daughter. And they never seemed to - sort of - rise at all. And there was always a certain amount of rivalry there, you see, the daughter there, my cousin, and my young
est sister, they both went in for a scholarship. My sister won and the cousin didn't. It was a great - it was great animosity for a long while - over that for instance, but that sort of thing, yes, went on but - she was always very - both of them were - a
s
 I say, they didn't want us to go through - their childhood as a matter of fact, you see. I mean my mother, although her mother was still living, her mother was one of those people that - although she had children hadn't any - time for them. And as soon a
s
 they were able to leave them at - twelve and thirteen they were packed off to live with someone else. And my father, his mother died when he was about - fourteen, fifteen I think and - consequently the whole family split up there again you see, and were 
d
istributed all round the village. So that they were determined that that sort of thing was not going to happen to us. Oh no, they were very - even when my sisters wanted to get married there was quite a - quite a to-do, as to - the - possibility of the yo
ung man - keep - when I got married, there was - oh dear, there was a terrible to-do, as to whether, you know, they could keep them - yes, whether they could keep them in the - the state they were used to and this sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What do you think they felt was the most important things in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Security. Something for a rainy day. And - well something for a rainy day, security was the - great thing. And - never to - owe people anything. Always pay your way. We never - I can't remember there being
 - of course, in those days - I mean there was a great deal of - what would you call - tallyman sort of - dealings. Men come round your door selling things and pay so much a week and that sort of thing. But - mother would never have that. Nor would father
.
 They used to say, if you want something, well - you've got to save up for it. And buy it with cash and not hire purchase or any of this sort of - they never would, although - in later life - they did get some things on hire purchase I know. But only smal
l things. But they were very - very strict on - on paying your way, never owing anybody anything and - being sure of a secure position.-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Which of the two would you say were more influential on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh I think mother was. Because she was the - she
 was the manager and she was the one that was always insisting and drumming it in. I don't think father worried himself too much about it. But - mother was the one, she was the more masterful - of the two people. More determined.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You say that you had these tallymen coming round, would you buy clothes from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well it was mostly clothes and household goods, linen and that sort of thing that they used to buy from them. We never bought anything from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Where did you get your clothes from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well we used to go to the - to the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You had new clothes did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Which might go a long way because - you see, we always had - sort of weekday clothes and - Sunday clothes. And Sunday clothes were always very carefully 
kept. You only had them on on Sundays. In the week - you'd have something - good and strong. And - sort of - long wearing. But - they were always new every time we had them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Quite a few of the people you knew would be wearing second hand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes. You'd - sometimes - we might have something made over. Only mother was rather - good with the needle when we were youngsters, but I can't remember me having any - sort of father cuts downs as the saying is. I know for my sisters she'd ver
y often make a dress out of something else, out of another dress and that sort of thing. But never for me, I was always - she'd knit. We had jerseys and that sort of thing you see. And of course coming home from school - you weren't - if you were going ou
t - on any of these little job or even - or even playing in the street, you didn't go out in the - clothes you went to school in. You'd have to - something a bit more worn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So really you had three sets of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, yes, you had three or four - three or four garments you could put on at a time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Shoes? Well - we didn't have so many shoes, we had Sunday shoes and weekday shoes. And father always used to mend those and he always used to do them up with Blakey
s, that's small pieces of - I don't know whether you know them - small pieces of iron perhaps about as long as that with long prongs on which could be nailed in you see and they used to come down the toe round the heel and round where the tread }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 came}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 . So that really the sole of your boot or shoe was - was iron shod really. You all - all had those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Where did you buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well you used to buy those at the local - leather merchants. Leather merchants you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did they have boot stores coming in at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes, you had boot stores. Oh yes. But - the - you'd go to the boot store to buy a new pair you see. But then after that I mean you didn't buy a new pair of shoes for a long while because father was always - always minding them, he'd
 go down to the local leather shop and buy a piece of leather you see about so big and quarter of a - whichever he wanted - whether he was mending his own or mine or somebody's. He'd come home with that and - well first it had to be soaked. Then he'd get 
o
ut his foot, I've still got his foot somewhere about the house, cast iron - sort of foot on a prong with went into a - a sort of pole and he'd get that between his knees, and boot on top of that, and then he'd - nail the leather on and trim it round and -
 so - mend the shoes you see. Mind you - sometimes - we used to - as youngsters we used to think they were - darned - clod hoppers, but - they used to last, they last a darned sight better than shoes do now as far as that goes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you tell me about washday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes, washday was always Monday. Oh yes, Monday was always washday. Cold meat and all the rest of it. Used to be a case of filling up the copper, and lighting copper fire. And that was of course the big old fashioned metal copper in the corn
er of the kitchen and - oh yes, everything had to be washed on Monday, and had to be ironed on - on Tuesday. Always had to be ironed and put away on the Tuesday. The place used to have - in the winter of course we used to have washing all over the shop. I
t used to annoy us as youngsters, no end. But - oh yes, everything had to be - household linen, clothes and everything else had to be - washed on - on Monday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about bathing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Bathing - bath night was always Friday night, or Saturday night, a
nd that was usually in the - kitchen, in front of the - in front of the fire. Until we began to - get up and - I myself and father, we used to go down to the public baths. Of course mother and my sisters, they'd - do things at home while we were out sort 
o
f thing, used to get chased out to - leave the house alone. But, until I was about - oh I suppose - twelve or thirteen - I used to bath at home. And change clothes of course, that was always Saturdays - Sunday mornings we always change into clean clothes.
 Always. That was the law of the means and persons and couldn't be - that couldn't be - changed by any means, oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You mentioned earlier that there were three bedrooms, did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, as far back as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have to go to bed at a fixed time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Yes. Let's see, it was - oh usually round about - eight o'clock I suppose. Until I was - oh seven - twelve, thirteen - fourteen, then it used to be nine sometimes be ten. I usually used to 
- you know, let me read the - let me finish this chapter. Oh well, if your father comes in and finds you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 here }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
- so - it was always a bit of a battle between nine o'clock and ten o'clock going upstairs to bed. But it was usually, I suppose, before ten, put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What did your parents think about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well - father used to be a bit profane, mother never did. Father - one of father's favourite expressions was bloody, but I don't think it was really as regards - regarded as swearing. It w
as just an emphasis more than - more than actually swearing. I never even heard him use other words, as one does, four letter words for instance as they're called nowadays. And I certainly never heard mother ever use one. In fact we'd get - we as youngste
rs used - said damn we'd get chased. Oh yes, she was very - although not church people and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your father ever do any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No, he - he didn't do any part time jobs at all in his - in his - life, as far as - only after he reti
red, then that was during - during wartime, not when we were children he didn't. No, there was nothing of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your mother didn't go out to work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, she didn't. She did one or two little jobs at times - at home, home job
s - yes, tennis balls and that sort of thing - but she never went out to work, oh no. As a matter of fact I don't think there were many people round about us that did really - no, they were mostly - - the home sort of thing. Widows might have done or - th
at sort of thing, but - at that time there wasn't much in the way of - women's work for married women really. Not when they had children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Where did you eat meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, we had - a - a kitchen which was our main meal - places, very seldom any othe
r room was used for - for meals except perhaps at Christmastime. Usually this kitchen was a small - smaller than this it's true, but it had the kitchen range in and opened into the scullery where the gas stove was and the water was. And so it was the most
 
convenient - in fact it was the main room which we all - mostly all lived in really. All our time - I mean there was a front room, but then, of course, front rooms were only used on sort of high days and holidays and special occasions. If - relatives arri
v
ed or - or called or something of that sort, then you'd - perhaps used the front room, or used to front room on a Sunday. But during the rest of the week it was always in this one room, everything was done there. Well - everything you could possibly think
 of, meals and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You mean on Sunday you had your meals in the front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
In the same room. In the same - in the same room. Except if anybody - we sort of had - any relatives that were staying with us or something of that sort. Then per
haps we'd use - a back sitting room, the sitting room that - sort of behind the - front room. Which - was really a dining room, but was very seldom used to tell you the truth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 That's a third room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes, we had - the house was - you came in the fr
ont door and you had a long hall which led to the stairs upstairs and then another hall - passage leading from that - oh off at a sort of - rather like that if you can under - follow me, which led into this - a kitchen. Well now there was a front room, or
 
a parlour as it used to be called. Then behind that there was another room. Then at the end of the passage was the kitchen and opening off that was the - was the scullery and - this kitchen had - had a door into the back yard and so did the scullery. Well
 
then upstairs - there was one big bedroom in the front, there was another bedroom behind that and then there was a third bedroom which came over the kitchen and scullery. And then the - behind the kitchen and scullery downstairs of course was the toilet a
nd the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 coal shed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and - various other out buildings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What was this middle room used for then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well - I suppose some people would have used it for as a dining room but we very seldom used it, except, as I say, at Christmas we might have - when we needed a larger table for - meals and that sort of thing. But otherwise we very seldom used it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So you had quite a lot of space, that was the last of the four houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 That was the last of the houses we were in, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 The second one, the one you shared?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would you again eat in a kind of living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Yes. That was a similar sort of lay out of the house, we had the front room and the kitchen, or at least a - a - well it was a kitchen really, which opened into a scullery. And
 then the other people had the room behind the front room which opened into the yard so that they could come round - through the yard into the scullery for their cooking and purposes you see. And then upstairs - there were three bedrooms. We had the front
 
room I think it was. The other people had the room behind it, and then we also had the third room which was again built over the - kitchen. They were mostly - mostly all houses were of that - of that type. You see. And we usually - with - when it was spli
t
 up, when there were two families in there well of case it was a case of making - the two ladies had to - sort of work things out between themselves as to how they used the cooking - facilities you see. Which sometimes in some - establishments rather caus
ed ructions but in ours I'm glad to say we usually got on very well together. And at Christmastime we'd - sort of - merge in together, and - do everything together and sit down together and we'd spend the whole evening together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So she had both a range and gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Could you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 describe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well - breakfast. When we were at school in the winter - I think the main dish was a large dish of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 Quaker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  oats. Mother - was a great believer in - something hot inside one and we used to
 get - Quaker Oats. Other time - the summer it would perhaps be bread and butter. Perhaps bread and dripping sometimes. We were always rather fond of that. - And - on Sundays - we would perhaps - have a boiled egg. Or perhaps a - half a rasher of bacon. B
u
t - the was only on Sundays. The rest of the week was just, a I say, bread and butter, tea - very seldom was there anything else, perhaps we'd have some jam or something of that sort. But it was just plain. Dinner was always a hot meal. Of - well - we've 
h
ad - at least, I say always a hot meal, I beg your pardon, Monday's was not, was cold. Because that of course was washing day and - was using up the Sunday - Sunday joint. On Tuesday the remains of the Sunday joint would probably made into a stew. On Wedn
e
sday we'd perhaps have - liver and bacon, fried or - pigs fry. On Thursdays - well it usually be a stew again. And Fridays - well Fridays was always a sort of - composite day, you never knew quite what was going to happen because of course it was the end 
o
f the week and pay day was - pay night was Friday night, and money in all probability was a little bit - short. But we always had - a hot meal. Every day. Saturdays again we'd have - a hot meal of - oh liver or bacon or - something of - something in that 
n
ature. But always there was a - there was a hot meal, my mother always believed in - perhaps the old saying of feeding the brute, and - we never went with - we never went without, it didn't matter how tight - money might have got towards the end of the we
e
k, there was something. In the winter, one of her - great things was, she always kept a large pot of soup on the hob. It often used to be my job to go over to the corner butchers - man we knew very well, lived in the same street - and get - twopenn'orth o
r
 three penn'orth of bones - and pieces, which always went into this stockpot. Well, no, they were very often - the - rind off - pork, and - bones and - bits of - all sorts - pigs tails, all sorts of things like that. But they always went into the pot with
 
- into the soup with plenty of - of - lentils and dried peas and things like that, and consequently we always had - a nourishing - a nourishing meal in that way if there was nothing else than that, with plenty of - of bread and - a large bread pudding aft
erwards, if you ever know that was, usually used to make up a jolly good meal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would you have this soup and meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No, if we had the soup - which was as much as you wanted really because it could nearly - you could nearly stand your - spoo
n up in it sort of thing. So that - there'd only be meat - soup and then say this bread pudding or - a jam tart, or something like that. Mother was always - she was always a good cook and always kept plenty in the - in the cupboard as far as she was able.
 There was nothing elaborate about it, but it was always good - what shall I say - good plain cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 And vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Vegetables, oh yes, there were always plenty of vegetables. Mostly - at one - at times, out of the garden. But - if not of cour
se they were from the local green - grocers, cabbage - cauliflower, potatoes, onions - well, pot herbs, which I often used to have to go and get. Pot herbs, well that's usually a mixture of - carrot, turnip perhaps a swede and - root - root - roots really
,
 which we - they used to call pot herbs, it was the general term, in the - in the trade, we often had two penn'orth of pot herbs. For tea, well that was we youngsters was bread and butter and jam perhaps. Sometimes - an egg, if we were good or sometimes j
ust the top off father's egg, whichever was the - favourite for the day, or who'd been good. And - sometimes }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 we\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 have fish like a - half a kipper, that we as children and grown - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 and father would have a kipper. Or - another thing - mother often used
 to do was specially on Saturdays, was haddock. I'd often have to go down to the market place and - get a haddock from - one of the - fish stalls, which was a well known noted man Or sometimes herrings. Sometimes we'd have - sprats, when sprats were about
. And - on Sundays we may have - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 shrimps}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 . E'd have to get up early and buy them from the - shri}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
p man that came round selling them live and have to cook them ourselves, boil them ourselves. Which always used to amaze us youngsters because you always bought 
them grey and when you boiled them they were either brown or pink. But - there was an old - old man, he was the chap he used to come round, he came from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 Gravesend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  really, he always dressed as a fisherman, blue jersey and always his seaboots and - a - a sor
t of sea yachtsman's cap, he always - always wore gold earnings in the lobes of his ear, I always remember that. And he always used to sell - sell these - those shrimps and - mostly Sunday mornings. No, the bell was always carried by the muffin man, that'
s
 another story. This - oh yes, we used to buy muffins, they used to come round, of course - that again was another Sunday morning thing, when the chappie would come round with a long tray of muffins on his head and his bell. Usually - you perhaps hear the
m on Sunday afternoons mostly, round - just the sort of - getting dusk, you would hear this bell and perhaps mother would say, oh let's some muffins, and one of us'd dash out and waylay him and - buy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 these}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  muffins which we then toast against the - the kitch
en fire or the open fire, whichever room we were using. That was rather - a sort of delicacy really. Sometimes we had winkles. That again was another delicacy. Or a treat. But - apart from that I don't think there's anything really special for meals. Exce
p
t at Christmastime of course, there was always - a bird. You see, in those days of course most of the public houses ran what they call - called a Christmas club, which you paid in sort of weekly whatever you wanted, and then according to the amount you pa
i
d in during the year at the Christmastime you either - at your choice, had a turkey or a goose and - usually a bottle of port, a bottle of whisky and - a bottle of gin. Well of course they were fairly cheap in those days. And a quart bottle of port used t
o
 cost you half a crown. A bottle of whisky would cost three and sixpence and a bottle of gin was - I don't think it was quite two bob. So that - really you hadn't - the - the bird was the most - expensive thing. As regards buying a - meat - well, during t
h
e week we used to use the - sort of butcher up the road. But on Saturdays it usually used to be a case of going down into the town, round about - seven or eight o'clock at night where you'd find all the big butchers would then be - sort of selling off the
 meat at auction. Or at least a sort of auction thing. And consequently you could very often get quite a big - a big joint at a very cheap rate. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 
Which reminds me also of those butchers at Christmastime, always used to have on the premises in the shop pinned up either prize or porker or a prize bull and it'd be there for about a week. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Sort of - and that would be killed say - two or three days before Christmas Eve and cut up and sold, that was a sort of - bit of an advert. And - as youngsters of course - yes -
 prize rosettes - as youngsters of course it always used to be the thing to go round and see the animals in the butchers shops. Another thing we used to have sometimes - for meals would be - things I don't think you hear much of now down - down South, tha
t
 is faggots and pease pudding. Faggots were - a mixture minced up meat and herbs, sometimes they were very highly flavoured, pease pudding of course was made from - pease and flour and - used to do down with the basin to the - one of the butchers shops. T
h
e one we used to go to mostly for those was a German butcher, we knew the man. In 1914 he - he got his - shop nearly wrecked because he was a German, although he hadn't seen Germany, I think since he was about - six months old. But - we used to go down th
e
re with a basin and a cloth and get these - about three pennorth or sixpennorth of - of - pease pudding, which would about fill the basin, - and - three or four faggots, and that would make quite a good - saveloys also we used to buy. Or saveloys, we usua
l
ly bought those on Saturday night if we were out with mother shopping - perhaps father would buy us a saveloy, hot saveloy, they used to sell them - sort of standing outside the shop with a - a heating arrangement to keep them hot. We had hone of those an
d
 you just had it in your hand and walk along the road eating it like a - a hot boiled sausage, but it was really a - really a lovely thing. But - apart from that I don't think there was anything really extra special about meals. Of course there was always
 cake. Mother always used to make a big cake for the week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Very little, mostly tinned fruit. I - there were tinned fruits, of course, in the shops, tinned foods, but they weren't bought by the ordinary people I don't think. You 
might get some people who considered themselves a little bit - aristocratic sort of thing - who would buy them, but - the ordinary people - our - my mother and father - about the only thing they did buy tinned would be corned beef. Which of course was fai
rly cheap - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 She did buy the tinned fruit as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh tinned fruit, yes, we often had tinned fruit. Tinned pears or peaches or pineapple mostly. But there wasn't a great deal done in - in tinned fruit I - well in our house at any rate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 There wasn't fruit in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well, yes, we had fruit from the garden, gooseberries and - blackcurrants and that sort of thing. Apples of course you could buy in the market, we bought - mother would always buy - oh rhubarb was another thing alway
s pulled out of the garden, which - we used to get dosed with much to our - sins. As a matter of fact, it's only quite recently that I've }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 begun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  to appreciate rhubarb again. But - mostly - mostly vegetables and that sort of thing were always fresh, fruit as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your mother did no bottling then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No, she'd make jam. But bottling, well in those days when I was a youngster of course bottling was a pretty tricky job. You hadn't the - appliances for it and so people didn't bottle so very much. It was 
mostly into jam. Even all my - aunts and that sort of thing in the country - it was always jam, they never - never bottled anything. Jam - you'd get everything turned into jam rarely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did she bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No, she never baked - never 
baked her own bread, we used to have to go to the bakers for that and of course that was always - usually a cottage loaf. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 
I don't know whether you - you've ever bought cottage loaf, like a - a sort of the bottom and the bit stuck on the top, and it was always sold by weight. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
And - usually you used to get an extra bit cut off another loaf to make up the correct weight. Always the - make weight we used to call it. Usually used to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 nibbled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  before we got home with the loaf. But - afterwards of course you use
d to get bread delivered and that makeweight disappeared. When I was - I can remember up to about - I suppose - twelve or thirteen - always going to get the bread, but after then it always got delivered. We had the local Co-operative Society or one of the
 
local bakers. But - it was like it is now I think, we often used to change bakers because - sometimes you get bread was absolutely O.K. and then suddenly it would - something about it we - we wouldn't like and we'd have to go to another - another bakers. 
Of course another thing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15017164  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 from}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 the bakers that - we used to do as children, which is nothing to do with the housekeeping, was - very often dive in for - a pennorth of stale cakes. That sounds as if we were rather starving, some youngsters I know, it was the o
nly way they ever saw cake. But - we used to do it perhaps if we were going - you know, we were out for a - on holiday, when - during the holidays and we'd gone out on the Common or something of that sort, we'd - call in a - a bakers and ask if they'd got
 
any stale cakes and perhaps have a pennorth just to - it was really - well I suppose - I thought we were giving ourselves a treat. But - whether we were or not I don't know, but any rate, it was something different than what we had at home. Then of course
 
we often used to - a ha'porth of broken biscuits was another thing, used to go to the local grocers for. They were sort of - sometimes we'd do that instead of sweets, when we had a penny or ha'penny or something of that sort. There was one thing I mention
e
d the other - didn't mention the other day - doing little odd jobs. One odd job we often used to do was - and that you can't do now - is we were often chased out with a bucket and - shovel, gathering up horse droppings -- for the garden. For father's gard
e
n you see. Well when we'd supplied him, we'd often, perhaps two or three boys would - go out with a bucket and shovel and we'd get a shovel full of manure and then go round knocking at doors, and sell it for a penny or tuppence. But of course that was one
 
way of making pocket money. I - used to do it quite - well, I say used to do it - I did do it and - it used to - sort of - put a penny or tuppence in my pocket, not very much, perhaps only get a ha'penny for a bucket full and you've walked round half a do
z
en streets, following horses round hoping they would sort of thing. And women used to do it, oh yes. If you saw it outside your house you see, you'd dive out and - grab it quick, sometimes there'd be an awful rush from both sides of the road, before - for
 
the garden you see. Oh it did. But of course it was - it was one way of manuring the garden because there wasn't the - the artificial manures you've got now you see. Well then of course horses have gone, you can't chase a car round - for what it leaves be
hind, it wouldn't do the garden much good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You did mention before about keeping hens and rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 There weren't any other animals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No. We - we - oh we had a cat of course, the usual - household - oh no, no, not fore e
ating, there were just the chickens and - and the rabbits, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your mother make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes, we'd always have to have - a large bowl - pots of - pickled onions. Oh yes, they were always made. Father used to - peel the o
nions, sometimes, and mother would do as well. But - we - I used to have to go and get the vinegar. But - apart from that I didn't have any - sort of part in - in making those. But she always made - she always made pickled onions - well pickled onions and
 
pickled shallots. Father always grew shallots in the garden for - for that one particular purpose. And they were always used of course for - well - meals when we had - perhaps a - a bread and cheese meal. Perhaps for supper. And we'd - we - well at least 
they would have them, the grown ups would have them and we as children didn't. We might have them in a - perhaps on a - well Friday, or sometimes on Saturdays we'd have bread and cheese and - and pickles. Which made a - quite a jolly good meal really.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did she make any drinks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Yes. In her later years, after - after we'd gown up - she used to make quite a great deal of - wine. We had a grapevine in the garden which spread round part of the house, which always gave a very good crop of grapes but you 
could never eat the things because they were so tiny and they very seldom ripened. But mother always used to gather those and - make wine with those. She'd also make rhubarb wine. And - damson wine she used to make, she'd buy the damsons. And there was al
w
ays, underneath the stairs was a sort of cubby hole cupboard, which was really intended to keep coal in, with the gas meters and things were in, and - packed in there were usually two or three casks of - of - some homemade wine, which - much to father's j
o
y because he was always popping in - well at least I say always, it sounds as if he was a drunkard, but - he - very often used to pop in just to see if it had - it had - matured. Consequently the wine usually - usually used to get drunk before it was real
ly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 matured}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
. But - oh yes, we had - used to have great games with that I remember on one occasion mother had bottled some and - made the mistake of corking it down. And we were all sitting in the kitchen one - one evening, and this cupboard was next to the k
itchen, it was only a party wall separating it, and suddenly there was an awful explosion, all these bottle burst. There were corks popping all over the place. But - oh yes, we always - always made wine and - and pickles. Oh yes, they were always done.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No, my mother didn't. But my great-grandmother did. Yes. Yes. I used to have to pick the herbs and used to get dosed - get dosed. Oh yes, we did make one medicine, I beg your pardon. We always used to, every spring, the
re was a big bowl of - a basinful of - sulphur made, up, treacle and sulphur, which we always used to get dosed with. This was flowers - powdered flowers of sulphur and - I think it was treacle used to get mixed in together and we used to get a large }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 dessertspoonful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of this thrust down our - you know, our mouths every Friday night during the spring. The rest of the year - we very - we'd get dosed with a horrible concoction called licorice powder. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 It was powered licorice - if it was really used as an aperi
ents, and we always had to have a dose of this on Friday nights or Saturday nights, and it was most horrible stuff because you mixed it up in water and - and when you drank it the stuff all stuck around your mouth and it took hours to get it out of your m
outh. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
The rows we - the - rows we kids used to kick up, my two sisters and myself, we used - used to end up in a crying match or something or the other over this but we always had to have it because if we didn't father used to threaten to pinch our noses an
d pour it in. That was worse than having to drink it. But - that was about all we used to do in the way of - of - the medical line really. Of course for other minor ailments we might get a - a poultice, mustard plaster or - or - or if we had earache we'd 
get possibly the - the centre portion of an onion, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 pickled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 onion popped in our ear hot. As a cure. Toothache - well, we'd perhaps get the gum rubbed with oil of cloves. Which used to burn like blazes and I don't know whether it was one counter - counter pai
n against another counter pain which sort of balanced things, but - I know I used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 suffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 very badly with - toothache. And - oh the amount of - oil of cloves I've had rubbed round my gum or had to rub round my gums was terrible. But - apart from that the
re was not much - we were fairly healthy as far as that goes, we never had - much in the way of doctoring. Of course the doctors then, you had to - you had to pay naturally. Luckily none of us were in hospital, except my mother was once and - I know then 
i
t was a case of - having to go round to - somebody we'd learnt of - lady who was a J.P. and had been on the council who - actually was the governor of the local hospital and - sort of - well scrounged a ticket - ticket from her. It was the only way in whi
ch really you could get - sort of - free - attention in hospital.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Was there a free dispensary or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, there wasn't - not in Woolwich, not that I'm aware of, I don't know of one there. No, it was usually a case of going round to
 a - to a doctor and of course - most of the doctors round about were sort of - doctors which - well they brought you into the world and they saw you out nearly, most of them. Although they've all gone now but - they all knew - well two of them I know kne
w my family, right through from beginning to - to end practically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Do you remember ever noticing your mother eating less at those times, like Fridays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes. I would say yes. Oh yes she did. That was I think - really. General - a general thing, I 
think you could say that mostly - even - not only on a Friday, she sometimes perhaps do it on a Thursday. But - I mean, she'd have - some - perhaps bread and butter while we were having - something else. It was, I think, a general thing with most - workin
g - working class wives - mothers really. It was always the children were - always came first. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did all of you eat together, including your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes. He came home for meals. The only meal we didn't have perhaps with him was b
reakfast. Yes, breakfast he'd be gone to work - but dinner, the lunch, midday, he always came home for because - of course working at the Arsenal we were only a few - few steps from it really. Tea, we always waited for tea 'til father came in. And - even 
- on Sundays, though Sundays, of course, breakfast we all sat down together because we were all home, father was home as well. But - and dinner we all sat down. Together, and tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have set places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes. The table was - sort of u
p against the wall, there was a dresser here, well the table stood out just in front so there was a sort of - a gap behind. Well my two sisters had to tuck in there. And - or sometimes I would. And father sat at the head of the table - mother at the foot,
 
with the tea tray and everything, and my two sisters possibly on the - on the side, and - or one sister and myself. Oh yes, we always had set - set places and - we usually used to lay the table. I would or my sisters would when they - they - got up, got o
n you see. But - oh yes, that was always one of the jobs we - we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did they have to quite a lot of helping in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well my sisters perhaps - did - perhaps do a little more in the house than I did, because of course it was their - what sh
all I say - their training really. And - of course - when I was say - twelve or thirteen, I was out sort of doing a little - little job or something of that sort, any rate I was getting out of those jobs. I'm afraid I was a - I was always get - trying to 
get out of something or other, I was always in trouble for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were you allowed to talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes, we weren't - we were not sat on in that way at all. Of course, we - we'd perhaps get choked off for - interrupting perhaps if fath
er was saying something or - if we started to argue between ourselves across the table - that - say May, my oldest sister had got a bit bigger piece of cake than I had, we'd perhaps have a little argument, or I wanted that and - that sort of thing. But we
'
d get jumped on then, but generally we were able to - talk to each other and - to mother and to father. There was never any - sort of children should be seen and not heard, in - on that occasion, of course there were others - when you used to get chased o
ut of the room or something of that sort. Or - shush, the children are about. Which often used to happen, well we - I won't say often used to happen but used to happen when - perhaps - my aunt from up the road came in or something of that sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What was their general attitude when grown ups were talking, were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh well, we were usually all ears. But - we usually used to keep quiet, and - oh I suppose you used to get bored really and - cleared off out. But you had to listen y
ou couldn't but in then if it was - a sort of outsiders - were - were in, you had to do as you were told really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have to eat a bit of everything that was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes, and that used to cause - that used to cause lovely argument
s, I remember - not so much with myself but I remember my sister, one of my sisters didn't like cabbage. And there used to be awful arguments. In fact - at one time if we didn't eat it - say for - dinner - it'd be kept until the next dinnertime and we'd h
a
ve - we'd get presented with it then. And - well that might go on for two or three days, until - we won usually. Oh yes, that - that often happened, we often used to object to something or other. And - and as I say, get presented with it quite a number of
 times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were there any special rules, table manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes, we had to - we had to hold our knife and fork properly and no elbows on the table and - sort of ask for anything you wanted passed to you. And - we usually used to get chased fo
r - perhaps eating a bit too quick. And - that sort of thing, yes, oh yes, we were - my mother was fairly - fairly strict and - as far - as far as that goes. You see, she'd - I suppose I learnt it in her young days in service - and in house - in house ser
vice and that sort of thing, and of course she considered that - well it was the thing. And - we were always - we were always made to behave ourselves at table. We could get down from table until we asked permission. You couldn't leave the table you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 But you could leave before the others had finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Oh yes. We often used to say, well can I get down, I want to go out and play or I want to go - something or other. We were always - usually allowed to. Sometimes we'd be made to sit, if t
here was anybody - with us having a meal well we'd have to sit - which - wasn't very - comfortable or enjoyable, just sitting there doing nothing sort of thing, nothing to eat. Just listening to other people - watching other people eat sort of thing.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Could you bring a book to the table or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
I used to - but usually used to get - a clout. I was always a - a terrible one for reading, I was always - mother was always yelling at me for having my head stuck in a book as she'd say. An
d if I did come to the table with a book well I usually used to get told to put the book away, and I used to say, oh yes, I will in a minute, and - I want to finish this page and - perhaps father would - very - very bluntly and emphatically tell me to put
 it away. But there was never any great trouble over it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your mother served the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did she serve them in a set order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Father first. And then - well I don't know there was any particular set order really but father was 
always served first. And - then I suppose it was - well I don't know whether I got served or my two sisters did, we - any rate we all got served. Oh sometimes we - oh yes, we always had the - dishes on the table. Yes. Except sometimes if mother was a bit 
-
 pushed for time like - something was cooking and - father'd come in - and of course he hadn't got a great deal of time, she might, if she was frying something, serve straight from the frying pan, or serve straight from the - soup pot. But usually everyth
ing was always put into proper dishes and - served that way you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 If you were hungry between meals could you have something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, hungry between meals, yes, we used to - have a - a piece of bread and butter or a - a piece of bread putting. A
nd that - reminds me of a story about the piece of bread pudding, which connects up with the - with the old boy that used to sell the shrimps. I'd come in one day from school and my mother was - mother was out. I went to the cupboard to cut a piece of bre
a
d pudding and for some reason or other the knife slipped, and it gashed me right round there, or at least on this hand, right round - no, it was - that hand, yes, right round practically - nearly severed the tendon between the thumb and finger. Of course 
i
t bled like blazes and I was only, I suppose about ten or eleven at the time. Nobody in the house, didn't know what to do, rushed out into the street, was standing at the front - gate, my hand smothered in blood when this old - fisherman came by. He saw -
 
saw my hand, grabbed me, wanted to know what I'd been doing, so - I said I cut it. Well he said, have you - where's the coal cellar? So I wondered what the man wanted. He grabbed - he held; my hand - wrist in a very tight grip, dragged me through the hous
e
 and I showed him where the coal cellar was, he opened the door and grabbed an awful big cobweb and slapped it on. And he said, where is your handkerchief? So I gave him my handkerchief, and he tied that on and he said, now don't take that off for - 'til 
tomorrow. Well I did, I left it on there and - do you know, the next day that had healed up. And there's no make on the hand at all. I - I really think he sort of saved my life but - with a filthy cobweb, smothered in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 coal dust}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 , but there was something abou
t the cobweb that - had a - a sort of - a stringent property and got the thing together. I always remember that, the cobweb and I've - I've never attempted to do it since; although I suggested to people they should do it. But - oh yes, we were always allo
w
ed to - well - allowed to have something between meals if we - if we wanted it, but not too much. We usually used to get told, oh you'll have your dinner in a few minutes, or something of that sort. But - we usually used to get our way, and have a cake an
d - or a piece of cake or a piece of bread pudding or a piece of bread and butter, whichever was - whichever was going.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You said you weren't chastised?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 By that you mean - a sort of beating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 But they would give you what you called a clout?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes, you got a smack at the side of the head.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Was that quite often really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well - yes, if - if you'd - were - sort of argumentative or wouldn't do - what you were told right away. It was merely a hit on the side of th
e head. Oh no, there was never - any - beltings sort of - some youngsters used to get I know. We used to have a cane at home. Oh we were always threatened with it. But - I can't say that - we ever got it. The only places - the only place I ever got the ca
ne was in school of course. But - that wasn't very often either, as far as that goes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What sort of things did your parents get angry about and punish you for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well if we - sort of - didn't do something - when we were told to sort of thing. Perhap
s it'd be a case of - you know, we'd - table we'd - perhaps bet a bit obstreperous, argumentative or something of that sort and - you'd be told - keep quiet or stop it or something of that sort and you didn't, well I'd usually end up with a - perhaps a - 
a smack you see. There was no - real - sort of - crime that you could say you got it for really. Just really being - not doing what you ought to do. In other words not behaving yourself, put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 How would you say that they expected you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh well, yes, respectfully and - obediently. That's the - the best way of summing it up really. You had to sort of - do things, I mean, if you were told to go to bed, which - of course in the summer one usually used to job against be
cause about eight o'clock at night when it was still daylight - well you sort of dawdled over it, you'd most probably get - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 clout}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and sent up, sort of thing, but - that's - that's about all really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about behaving to your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh well
 we used to have our little squabbles, between - between us. Especially when I was - say - let's see, they - they were of course most - younger than me, there's - what - bout four or five years difference between the - myself and my oldest sister, and my 
o
ldest sister had - was a bit independent. My youngest sister - was - was mother's favourite and they used to - have a terrible habit of - pinching my things. The sort of ties - and that sort of thing, and - we'd perhaps have little squabbles over that. Bu
t - we were - quite a - a friendly, cheerful family, with not a great of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They didn't interfere between you and your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, yes, we'd probably get told to stop it and that sort of thing, and perhaps that was where we - get more clouts th
an anything else, but not very often really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What did they say if another child hurt you, should you hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Oh yes. Father always said, go and hit - go and hit him back. But - usually used to keep out of those things, not - tha
t didn't happen very often. I can't remember having any real good fights. As some youngsters do have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you remember birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes, well we never made much - much of birthdays really. I mean, there were never any birthday presents, or - birth
day parties. And nothing really special was done about birthdays. They were usually - presents and that sort of thing were usually confined to Christmastime. There was really no - no fuss or bother made about it, it passed over in the ordinary course of e
vents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you describe Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes, well Christmas - well before Christmas of course it was always a case of - as youngsters we always used to go round the shops because then of course they - always decorated shop windows up in special way
s. For instance I can remember one shop even now - when they had all their windows, each window was - decorated as a suite of - as a room. Set out as it would be in a - sort of - very well to do house. You'd have - the - the kitchen with all the - eatable
s
 and things all spread round. Of course it was advertising goods sold by the shop of course. Then you had the next room - perhaps a bedroom with all sorts of - beautiful things spread around. Then you had a dining room, you had all the - the dummies - dum
m
y figures dressed as if it was a party and you had the streamers all round and everything else. Then of course there were the toyshops. There weren't so many of the mechanical things that you have now. But of course we always used to go round surveying al
l
 the toy shops, choosing what we - what we would like and possibly never get. And comparing prices and all this sort of thing. And then of course we always used to ed up about a week before Christmas with buying a - packet of - chain paper, that was strip
s
 of coloured paper, we - and we used to take them home of course and persuade mother to make us some flour paste, and then we used to spend hours in the evenings - making the - taking these strips of paper, bending them round into a circle, sticking them 
t
wo ends together, and then putting the next one through and so making a chain. So that we could decorate the house. That was really the - sort of only way you could get decorations at that time, later - of course they did start selling - the rather - fanc
y
 - paper chains which were cut out of paper and they spread out. But we always made our - as - as youngsters we always made our chains, and then - Christmas Eve, well I usually used - used to have to go out with - with mother shopping, because as I mentio
ned she was deaf and she couldn't hear in the noise. But on Christmas Eve night usually about nine o'clock, we'd go down - I'd go down with my father perhaps to the market - to - get the - oranges and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 nuts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and that sort of thing. The market of course used to be all lit then with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 naphtha}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 flare lamps and it used to be a wonderful exciting sight to youngsters. They used to put their stalls out about - two days before Christmas Eve, and set them all out and then they'd - they'd sleep beside them all - all the ni
ght, to keep them going, and of course it was always a bustle and - there was all sorts of things - on sale. All sorts of novelties and things of a penny and - that sort of thing, but - was really a - a wonderful world of delight really Christmastime then
.
 Christmas Day of course well, Christmas Eve we'd - when we went to bed we usually hang up - a stocking and - Christmas morning of course we'd - first thing we'd do was dive for the stocking as soon as we woke. What we'd usually find, an orange and some n
