own fun. We used to join in when we were sharing the house with the other people, we used to all join in together, and - the man of the other family, he was an ex-sailor as a matter of fact, an ex-Naval - Royal Navy, and he used to have a - always remembe
r
 this because it happened every year and we never got tired of it, he always used to go out and take myself and his own son, we were both about the same age, and he'd do us up in sheets like choirboys and do up like a - a vicar, and we'd always march in, 
i
n procession, and then he'd start - what he called a - a recitation. And I can remember the thing now. It always started off - it was a dark and stormy night, and the wind howled dismally, and the chief of the brigands said unto Antonia, Antonio, tell us 
a
 story. And Antonio's story was - it was a dark and stormy night and the wind howled dismally, and the chief of the brigand said unto Antonio, Antonio tell us a story. And so it went on, until we used to throw things at him to make him stop. But - that wa
s
 always done on Christmas night. And the rest of that, well we used to just - play games perhaps sing, we had no music in the house. There was no musical instruments in the house but we used to - do something or other. And then usually about midnight on C
h
ristmas night we always decided, the whole lot of us, would always go out for a walk, children and all. And - oh we'd perhaps walk round the streets and across - a nearby common which used to be quite exciting for - for us youngsters. Not only of course t
