I couldn't say definitely, I know he belonged to the Conservative club. And I think a condition of that was that you belonged to the party. So that he might have belonged to it that way, but I never really - really knew
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did he ever canvas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No. He never took any active part. Oh no, there was - he never did - never did anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Do you know what your mother's views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well - of course - before }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 suffrage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  I - and even afterwards I suppose she was just the same as 
father, she followed father. I think everybody did then, wives usually used to - vote according to their husband and - children used to follow suit really. I mean, elections we used to - sort of join in as youngsters, we usually - the local candidate'd ha
v
e a - a wagon going round all bedecked with his posters and - we kids used to get rides in it and sing - you know, vote, vote for - somebody or other. We used to think that quite high - high delight. And I must say that elections were much more - exciting
 things then than they are now. And of course they lasted much longer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you go to listen to the poll being declared then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, because it usually used to be very late. Usually used to be in the early hours of the morning, I can't - I don't know
 that father ever did. Oh - once they did. I wasn't - I wasn't present, because I was in the Army, but I know - it was during - it was after the war I think was over, the election then, they did all go down to the local - local Conservative club - and - t
h
ey had sort of party in the early hours of the morning and - they defeated the local Labour candidate, and I know all the Labour party people, so they told me, all advanced on the Conservative club and were going to raid it. And - this Conservative club h
a
d a very big - the bar had a flat roof, so that you could get on it you see and it faced the street. And I know all the men and they barricaded the ladies in the dance hall and got onto this roof, with all the missiles they could, including - including a 
c
ouple of fire hoses. But as I say I wasn't here, so I don't know, but it was - it was - I think about the first election after 1914 - after the 1918 war was over. When things were getting a little bit - but of course we had been Labour, we had been a Labo
u
r Borough before then. Because - one of the very first because Will Crooks was - was our member for some years. And I think before then it had been Liberal. Really. And of course as you say - mentioned, that poster, was a Liberal poster, it's quite possib
l
e that father might have been Liberal then, and - possibly was because - of course a lot of the Liberals did become - did come over to the Conservative party. It might have been then that - change over came. But - as I say, I wasn't particularly intereste
d in politics then as a schoolboy except - for the excitement really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 There were people at that time who sometimes felt that pressure from their employers to vote one way or another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, it didn't apply in father's way because of course he was in government employee you see, in Royal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 Arsenal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, and of course it didn't - it didn't affect. I agree with you, in - in the - in the country it would. I think - most of my uncles for instance were farm workers, would naturally vote - Conservative - because 
of course - they had to keep their jobs, and I think that gave rise to an argument father always used to come out with that - the ballot was never secret. Oh he always used to say that. But of course, the thing is, I think it came from - the countryside o
f him, where of course - I mean - people naturally voted according to their - according to their job. And so it gave rise to that. Oh yes, he often used to say that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You mentioned about different clothes and food on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your parents think it was wrong to play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh no. No, no. We used to get - we used to play, but - we were usually chased off in - the afternoons to - Sunday school. Oh yes, that was very strict. I did of course - my young sisters didn't when the
y were sort of babies, but afterwards they used to go to the same Sunday school, it was - a very low Evangelical affair I know. Most of the - teachers, and the people that ran it - were - oh Baptist or something or other, they used to hold - outdoor meeti
n
gs, I know, religious meetings I know, they were nearly all, strange to say, foremen in the Royal Arsenal. But - they used to look after us quite well and we always used to have a very good - Sunday school treat. Far better one that - the church Sunday sc
h
ool did. Although we never went out of the - out of the Borough. The two leading lights of the - school who we very seldom saw were - an very old couple, an old Colonel and his wife who lived - in a very gig house on the top of Shooters Hill, it had a lot
 
of ground, meadows and that sort of thing. And consequently our Sunday school treat always used to be there. But it - the Sunday school was held in the school, in the same street as I lived in, and the school I used to attend in the week. And - we always 
u
sed to assemble there in the morning of the school treat you see, all with our - tickets on, and usually with a - with a brown mug, and - then we'd all form into procession and usually with a band, they usually used to get a band from somewhere, and the t
o
ddlers were always in somebody's - coal cart cleaned up for the day, and off we'd process all through the Borough, it - was all uphill all the way, to this field. Then we'd have - sports and a jolly good tuck in and all this sort of thing. But in the even
i
ng, I always remember it, because - the main - the road to go part of the way was merely a cart track then but is now a - a well made road, and we always used to come - be dished out in the evening and - forming up in procession with long canes with a Chi
n
ese paper lantern on with a candle in it, and the candles were always lit and we all used to go - time this so that it was just dusk. And then the whole of us, somewhere about three hundred or four hundred youngsters and grown ups - would all process back
 
to the school, through three streets with all these lanterns, it used to be a wonderful sight. And all singing at the same time. It was usually - a great day. And as I say, it was far better than the - church school, I remember we once - changed over to t
h
e church Sunday school, because we thought they were having a better - better - treat and their treat was to a place called Riddlesdown, which is out near Croydon. Well - we went on this treat. Went by train as a matter of fact, which was a great thing of
 
course. Well when we got there it was just a - an open expanse of country and - oh - were herded into a barn for tea and it wasn't much of a tea like we used to get in the other place, sitting on the grass, and I - if I remember rightly it rained. So we w
e
ren't impressed with the church Sunday school and we never - never went there again. But - oh we went to that Sunday school for years. In fact I think I've still got upstairs somewhere a Bible which was presented me as a first prize from there - for somet
h
ing or other. But - oh yes, we went there fore - for years to - to that school. In fact I think I went there until - well I left school really. 'Til I was about fourteen. And my sisters carried on after me and I knew quite a number of the - the people tha
t ran it, of course as I say, they were mostly foremen and of course - there here was a social structure in Woolwich which was rather - peculiar. At least, I won't say peculiar, it was perhaps natural. Woolwich of course depended on - the Army, it was a }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 garrison}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 town, on the Royal Arsenal and the Royal Dockyard, Woolwich Dockyard which was merely store more than anything else of the Navy. Well - the town really had been built around the barracks and the Arsenal. The Arsenal stretched a long way along the riv
er. And of course the old town had - gone along with it. Well that older part of the town was merely really occupied by the - the ordinary workmen, the working class as you might as well say. And it extended up - to - the - up by the barracks, I mean wher
e
 my house was we were all ordinary working class. Quite a lot of the people were ex-service - ex-soldiers who'd come out and settled - come out of the Army and settled there you see. And - as you went up Shooters Hill, which was - in the middle of the bor
ough, you got newer houses, and they were mostly occupied by the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 artisan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, the - mechanic and the foremen. Until - after - well say about 1905/6, they began to build on the other side of Shooters Hill, which was still in the borough, in a place called 
Eltham, they began to build that up and the - people that were in better jobs moved out to there, you see. And consequently Woolwich itself, round about the Arsenal, and the dockyard, became - slummy. There's no doubt about that. But as you gradually came
 
up the hill so you got away from that. And got into - a perhaps - houses that were running down. And then you gradually went up. Here and there you'd get an isolated patch - of houses - which were - had - when they were first built were sort of away from 
the - on the suburbs of the town as it were, which were occupied by whole families who were - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 in fact. But they gradually moved out. And of course - again, you had Woolwich Common stretching - from the barracks right up to Shooters Hill, and that was lined with old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 Georgian}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 houses which unfortunately they're pulling down now, they were all occupied by - officers. Well of course officers in those days were - moneyed people, and of course that was the scene of - what shall I say, the society life
 of - of Woolwich. Then you had. The Royal Academy which again was the student officers, again moneyed people. And - so on, and the barracks themselves were - well sort of isolated area and of course occupied by all - infantry - well all branches of the -
 the Army.
