\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 As a child how far do you think you would have been aware of all these differences?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Will, you were aware of the fact that up the hill people were perhaps better off than you were. You see. You were certainly aware of that, I was always aware of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You were half way up the hill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 We were partly up the hill, we were on the edge - of the older part of the town. But as you went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 further}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  away - and I was mentioning about - delivering newspapers. Well most of those deliveries wer
e up the hill you see. In this - what shall I say, people who were perhaps - perhaps better off, perhaps they weren't. But you would - you could always see it because - they had - bigger newspaper bills, for instance, they had magazines and - all this sor
t of thing you see. Then again - another job I had was in the local grocers shop and off }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 license}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, delivery boy, well you - you recognised it there, because you have - people - who would - order - instead of going out to the pub they order it. Consumed at ho
me sort of thing. You see, it was a little bit too - not quite the thing to go to a pub. There again, you have people - which - you always recognised were the snobs as we used to call them, who'd order - quart bottles of burgundy, Australian burgundy at t
h
at by the way. There was man - and - you - you'd notice them too from a question of dress. In a street just near me which had - which was bigger - much bigger houses - there was one man who often - I worked under him afterwards - well you always used to s
e
e him going to work about nine o'clock in the morning always in a morning coat. You see, he was - a manager of a department in a furniture store. I don't think - I don't think he got such an extraordinary screw, but he always - went in a morning coat. Exc
e
pt in the summer when he'd wear an alpaca coat, and a straw hat. But he always carried a walking stick, and he always had a gold watch chain. And another thing you always noticed too - that if those people ever did go into pubs - they'd never go in a publ
i
c bar, it was always in the saloon bar, you see, you wouldn't - you - you'd always tell there was a - a difference. I remember this man particularly because - it was - it was to his house I used to have to - always take round - what was it - a dozen Whitb
read stout and a quart bottle of burgundy. Man named }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13920496\charrsid15017164 Nelson}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
. As I say, I came to work under him afterwards. - But you got that, and then of course in the town itself - a lot of the big - big draper - big drapers shop principally, their staff lived in. Lived
 on the premises. As single people. And they were always dressed in black. Oh yes, the women had to be dressed in black while behind the counter. Oh you couldn't wear colours there. It was not until - oh I don't know - oh a long while after the war that -
 people were allowed to dress out of black. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you have any contact with those living in the shops?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes. We did get in - get to know somebody there once. And - but they were never very happy there as far as that goes, they always had to
 be in by nine o'clock at night, even when they - even though they may be - fifty. They had to be in nine o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were you brought up to treat these different sorts of people in different ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well you were always - brought - brought 
up to sort of - pay respect to - other people. I mean, you weren't - you weren't expected to cow tow to them. But - well anybody older than yourself - you were always sort of - expected to - address them as sir if you ever did - in fact I do now as a matt
er of fact. Just with sheer habit. But, you weren't - it was never sort of rammed into you that there was any - difference in status. But you could sense it, you could see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 It's not like you said in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no, in the village was diffe
rent, but of course of course there you were - you were more of a - a tied - a tied community. You see you were tied to your farm cottage. And - and that sort of thing. But in town, no - there was not - not that but - you always did know there was a - a d
i
fference, and you sort of always - did - yes - you did - sort of treat them with a certain amount of respect you know. I remember one young - young - youngster when I was at school, he asked me to go round to his house. Well his father was a foreman in th
e
 Arsenal and I went round, and oh dear, I was the most - I - I recognise it now, I had most uncomfortable and he had a most elaborate train set which I never in my wildest dreams possessed. And - mother fussed around. Mother was beautifully - nicely dress
e
d in the afternoon and all this sort of thing. But - I only went there about twice because I was so uncomfortable, you see. You got - people who were that way did try to ape something else, really. You did, you felt it, oh yes. Oh yes. And I do now. I mea
n, all - all the - the pretentiousness - it actually annoys me. I love to - take them down a peg if I can.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would there be anyone who would call your father sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh I don't think so. No. There was only us as youngsters used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Would another boy call your father sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes, I think other boys would - the same as among ourselves. If you would - is - somebody older - or if you didn't call him sir you'd call him mister, you see. You' always give him the title or mister at any rate. I doesn't matter who it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you think that the big gulf was really between the foremen and the rest or between craftsmen and labourers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well I should say there was a - a gulf between fore - foremen and - and the craftsmen. And then of course a -
 between the craftsmen and the labourers, because of course the foreman was the boss as far as that goes, you see, in the - in the Arsenal. And - I suppose would have been in any other firm really. So there was a - a certain - gap between them, in - in st
ructure, in social structure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 How would you define the lower group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 The - coster}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and the - oh the slummy part, well you just - you just regarded them as - sort of - ne'er-do-wells, not worth - thinking about really. I mean, there you did - aroun
d - one very old street in - in Woolwich, which was right against the Arsenal, called the Warren, which had been the original site of - of the Arsenal, which was a terrible slum, and along the waterside, of course - you got a lot of people employed on the
 river - bargemen and that sort of thing. And of course the river was greatly used then and much more than it is now. Well there they were considered the roughest of the rough, really. And - very often they were, they were real - rough 'uns. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 And that's - th
at's still - I think to a certain extent - applies even now, because we always used to - you always used to consider - I mean people talking would always sort of consider that - we were a little bit better than people that lived in North Woolwich which wa
s now on the other side of the river - they were mostly dockers and that sort of thing and they were considered absolutely rough and we were much better than them, sort of thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
You see, there was always that - sort of little difference. I don't say it was - very pronounced but - you always - in conversation and that sort of thing, oh those rough people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were there families whose children you weren't allowed to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No I don't think so. I can't recall anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You were talking about these poorer people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes, we always - they always used to regard them as - rough and - very much - out of - the running, sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you think of a family that you knew at all that you felt were rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, I don't think we had 
much to do with them. I didn't know anybody in that part of the world. Or in that part of - Woolwich or London. You used to get some people that were - sort of regarded as - rather - low, I remember people next door to me. But they were quite nice people,
 
they were very big family, and the mother was rather a feckless sort of woman. The father was a man who was - well immersed in Radical politics - and after became a Labour man, and - he - was also - had in his younger days organised excursion - train excu
r
sions to Yarmouth and one thing and another. Well they were a family that were always sort of - in debt. They were always popping in wanting to borrow something and something of that sort. And they were - I know mother used to regard them as being rather 
-
 not quite - the thing. You see, you used to get that but as regards the - the waterside people - there were - I didn't - we didn't know any of them but we used - to see them of course. And you used to get the youngsters running about in ragged trousers a
nd perhaps - no shoes and socks, as far as that goes. I mean, that did happen and - but only in that sort of - milieu really. Actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Who would you feel were the most important people in the area where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well the most important people in the borough of course were the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 
trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, I - I should say, the shopkeepers and the - and the moneyed people who lived in the bigger houses, and then again I suppose you - form - from sort of - building up society you'd call the - the Army of
ficers again were - considered sort of up there. Although they were - a collection on their own actually. Rather separate and - than mixing in with the civilian you see. But as regards the civilian population I suppose - the most important people were the
 - the big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  who had money. Were able to have their - carriage and pair and - live in a fairly big house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you feel at that time that it was possible to move up from one class to another, or to move down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Very I - I suppose it was 
always dinned into one that by becoming a white collar worker you'd moved up. You see, and it was always - not exactly dinned into me but - I know it was always mother's ambition that I should have been a - a white collar worker and - somehow or other it 
w
as always my own ambition. I wanted to - I don't know whether I was - I can't say that I was extra brainy but I always thought I wanted to use my - my brain more than - my brawn sort of thing. I had no aptitude for - for hand work at all, at school I used
 
to hate metal work and woodwork were the two - things that used to drive me to drink. I always - I can never see the sense of having to go to school and - and - go - spend an afternoon - filing away at a - iron bar to make it into a square one. It always 
u
sed to be - seem to me to be a waste of time, but - it was the other side of - of school that I was more interested in, and then - not so much the mathematical side but the art side, the arts have always - the arts side, have always interested me more tha
n
 anything else, because at school I often used to - get - when we had assembly I'd suddenly find the headmaster reading out one of my essays or something of that sort to the whole assembled school. Much to my annoyance or - otherwise. And - for the last s
i
x months I was at school I spent - every day sitting by myself in the hall, not undergoing tuition at all but - drawing - maps for the school. Illustrating - various campaigns like Prince Charlie's march through England and - Marlborough's marches through
 
- Europe and Napoleon and that - those - those maps were hung in the school for - oh years after I left. That was my - my side of it. Mechanical side I never was and I - I'm no good now at mechanicals. Really if I try to saw a piece of wood I can never sa
w it straight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Was there anyone at that time who was said to be a real lady or a real gentleman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No, I can't recall - anybody really that was - that didn't have to work. That had a sort of private income was always regarded as a lady or a gentle
man. And there were some round about us. But we knew - by name but not personally, because they were always considered - right out of the - out of this world sort of thing as far as we were concerned. But they were always helpful when it came, as I say, i
f you went to the hospital to - get a governor's ticket or something of that sort you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Did you notice the difference between the people - was it mainly the foremen who went to the chapel - do you feel there was a difference in church and chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well - no, I won't say that, it was only the case that - this particularly Sunday school were mostly all chapel people. I can't say that - there was any - any - church - division of church and chapel among the foremen really, I think they were all mixe
d up, actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 On the whole the church congregation didn't strike you as being different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh no. Oh no. No. Except that the - chapel people were a little more severe in their outlook towards life and - would - very often - bring religion to con
versations when - it wasn't necessary and that sort of thing. But - I don't think there was any great deal of difference between them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about the Catholics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh well, the Catholics were - there were plenty of them in Woolwich, just below us a
t the bottom of the hill there was a Catholic church, and - well - it was never regarded with much favour. They were always considered the poor. We had Catholic neighbours next to us. And - next door. And - there was not much - sort of social intercourse 
b
etween us and them. Although - their children grew up - with us. But - they were Irish as a matter of fact. And - all the - all the Catholics were considered a little bit - well - you know - really. I think it was more a case there of - of religious preju
dice than anything else, actually. Because I remember - in the Woolwich dockyard, when I was a youngster, they had a church there, a Church of England church, which was high church, and they started - using }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 incense}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and having processions round the outside o
f the church and everything else and there was nearly a riot. You see, it was more a - it was more a religious prejudice than it was - a social prejudice really, actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Was there much sort of criminal activity in your parts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, I don't think
 so. You'd get plenty of drunks and disorderlies - on Saturday nights, when - they used to - a thing you never see nowadays - when they used to - if there was somebody was so drunk and incapable they couldn't walk they'd send for the bier and tug him on t
h
e bier, strap - wrap him up and cart him off to the police station that way. They had a bier which was by the way was like a stretcher on wheels, and it had a hood over one end you see, which came right over. It was usually used - for taking bodies found 
in the river to the mortuary. But on Saturday nights it was nothing to see a couple of policemen wheeling this thing through the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 town}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and you knew they'd got somebody drunk and incapable in it. You'd get that, and you'd get perhaps a - a little bit of thieving. But - nothing like there is at the present moment. Nothing like it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You say you used to run away from the policemen, did you see them around much at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. 'h yes, you always saw policemen about - always on patrol. And you did regard
 them more as - a sort of friend than you - they do now. Oh yes, there was always the policeman about, even at night. You always see him at night with his - little lantern on his belt and his - cape - with a cape rolled up and slung on the other side of h
is belt. Oh yes, you always saw them and - in daytime and night and - they were always patrolling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 And they used to discipline the children much more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well - I won't say they actually disciplined them but - if they found you getting up to mischie
f - and caught you they - they might give you a jolly good talking to or they might give you a clump. But - they didn't actually put themselves out to do it. You see. It was only just incidental if they came across it. But I mean - we used to get up to mi
s
chief and all sorts of things. I mean, go scrumping and one favourite game at school was - of course most houses being a terrace the doors came together with just a short fence or wall between them and one of our great delights was in one particular stree
t
 was to - go and tie the knockers of two houses together, or tie the letterboxes together, and then knock at each house and then run and hide behind somewhere and watch and see the two dear ladies both come to the door to open the door and of course - one
 
would open her door a little bit and - pull the other one shut, and she'd give it a tug and the finish there'd be an awful game. Things like that, or we used to - scrumping or - pinching somebody's - pinching apples off somebody's tree over the garden fen
ce or something of that sort you see. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you remember any other practical jokes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes, spreading cotton across the - across the street. And - also - dropping - say dropping a handkerchief - bit of cotton - tie the cotton and then somebod
y goes to pull it up you jerk it away. Or - calling out to a carman going by - whip behind, because - of course that was one our great jokes, used to jump on a - on a cart that was going by, have a free ride, sort of hanging on the tailboard, and - of cou
r
se it usually used to be the cry, whip behind, and of course he'd swish his whip round you see, and perhaps it might catch you, it might not. And - well we used to go along - used to see shops, newsagents specially, that had their boards out with all the 
- flyleaf - placards of each paper on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 It}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 was nothing for us to run along and nick those so that they all came down with a clatter as we ran - as we ran by. Oh things like that, but I don't think we had any - really dangerous ones. We used to - climb the la
mp post and swing off the - of course lamp posts weren't so \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid920634\charrsid15017164 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 the gas lamps, and we always used to have bars standing out and we used to climb up - those and hang on that and swing. We used to use the lamp post as a wicket for cricket. Of course
 sometimes the ball would perhaps go through somebody's window and then you'd run like mad. Or we'd play football in the street, we usually used to perhaps get chased by a policeman for that. But most of our games, well they were seasonal games, there was
 
- hoops in the winter. And we used to run up and down the road with a - boys with an iron hoop, the girls with a wooden hoop and a - a hook which we used to skid them along. Then there was - marbles which we used to play up - the - either up the gutter on
 the way to school, or - on the pavement with a ring of marbles and flicking them in. Then there was - ciggies, or cigarette cards, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 ciggies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  - cigarette cards, which we used to flick up and try and knock down as many as you could and that sort of thing and w
in the other fellow's sets. There was Jacky fivestones, which was fivestones, we used to have all sorts of weird and wonderful rhymes. Playing with those, catching them on the back of your hand. Cherry stones. Another one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you play with your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No, no. No, no. If I did play out in the street it was usually with a crowd of boys. Oh and then there was cops and robbers. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 Or as it became after the cinema came in it became - Cowboys and Indians. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 It usually }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 used}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  to be called cops and robb
ers when I was a boy, mostly. And - things like that we used to get up to, and of course we'd go up onto - onto the common and perhaps play cricket. Or at least try to. Although I was never much for any of those - sports as far at that goes. I remember, b
e
ing out with one crowd ones - number of us in the street - during holidays, we went up onto the common and - on the common there was one place, it was a lake surrounded by bushes and fence, which was used for - as a swimming pool actually. But in the dayt
i
me you could go in there and I - we were in there and I remember I got pushed in this day, clothes and all. Any rate I went down for the third time 'til somebody pulled me out. Any rate, after that we - came from there to be a school playground which was 
kept open - during school holidays because they had - a swings and a - a great pole with a lot of ropes hanging down that you put your arm through a loop and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 swing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  round and swing yourself off the ground, a maypole sort of thing. We all got over there and I
 remember somebody threw a cricket stump and point hit me in the temple, gashed me. That was the same afternoon. And - well I don't think - I think I went home after that one. But ; I mean, we used to do things like that but - oh we used to get up onto th
e
 common - on Thursday after - evenings, the band - used to have a band play in a bandstand on this common and just near it was a - near the bandstand was a hollow with a lot of gorse bushes in and we used to very often get there and play - cops and robber
s and hide and seek and all sorts of things like that. But - that's about all I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your mother mind if you get your clothes dirty?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well, she'd grouse at us. But - as long as they were going in the wash and that was - I don't drink she really objected too much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You didn't belong to any youth clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No. There weren't any then. Oh there was, I beg your pardon. There was a - a sort of Band of Hope if you can call that a youth club. I did go to that - once or twice. It used t
o be held in a - in a building which was a Carmel chapel. It's a very low sort of Baptist chapel, it's now - it's now the parish hall of local }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 Roman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
