it meant - paying out for uniform and all the rest of it. There was one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Nothing at the church or chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, there was no youth - whatsnames there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No I never - no, it's years afterwards I belonged to the choir. There was
 one other - thing I was taken to, I think that was just after I left school though. About 1913 was a sort of literary society run by a chapel, somebody who knew me got me to go along one night to a musical evening, and it was the first time I ever heard 
- any Gilbert and Sullivan. It was done on gramophone records with a - you know, gramophone, which was a box with clockwork in it to work the turntable and the sound came out of a great big horn. The - records were of Pirates of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 Penzance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and the Mikado, and
