\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 When did you get to the cinema more regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh - after I left - left school and started to wo
rk. But then, of course, there weren't - weren't any cinemas really. I can remember the first one opening in Woolwich, was after I started to work, and was about early 1914 I think. When - of course you went in the vestibule and - it was all done up with 
p
otted palms. And you went in the afternoons, you paid sixpence to go in, and in the programme that sixpence entitled you to a free cup of tea and biscuits. And I always - the long - the first - sort of long reeled film, five reels I think it was - the fil
m
 was called Tilly's Punctured Romance. It was a real slapstick comedy. But of course in those days you got one reel, then you had to have a stop while the - whatsname changed the reel you see. And - and so on. That cinema's now destroyed, it was destroyed
 during the war, it was hit by a bomb. But - it was - there weren't many about you see. They were only just sort of coming in really as cinemas. You got the bioscope which was - which was really a - a fairground and traveling showman sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 And concerts?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Concerts, no, unless we went to hear - the band concert on the common on the Thursday evening, or we listened to the - Royal Artillery band on Sunday mornings after church parade, they used to usually give a selection of music outside the
 officers' mess. And public were always allowed to go up and see the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 padre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
, as a matter of fact it was one of the things to do in Woolwich - on Sunday mornings, and we used to stand - stand and - listen to that, but as regards other concerts - no, I can't 
remember going to a concerts to all. Well, the parade - they - they used - all - all the various regiments - and units in the town, in the garrison, used to parade in full dress for church service at the garrison - church - and it was the thing to do was 
t
o go up on the parade and you stand along the parade and watch them marching into church. Then you just parade up and down the sort of monkey parade we used to call it, when the boys used to get off with the girls and that sort of thing, and then after ch
u
rch service was over they'd all come out form up, and then they'd ceremoniously march off - taking - the - one of the Colonel's or the G.O.C. taking the salute you see. Then - after they'd cleared off, the officers were all drift into the mess which opene
d
 onto the parade ground - for their gin and tonics etcetera and - the band would play a selection of music, usually a - they used to do one or two sort of standing in a circle, then they'd do a sort of ceremonial - one of these marching affairs when they 
m
arch in between each other and all the rest of it. Then after they'd gone over the thing was you went to the end of the parade ground - and waited for the one o'clock gun to fire. They always fired a - a - a time gun at Woolwich until - about 1918 - no, 1
9
14 I think it was - at one o'clock, which was the signal for all - during the week, they used to fire it during the week as well, which was the signal for all the - shops to close and the - factories to - knock off for lunch and all the rest of it you see
.
 But we always used to go along there and of course it was always a case of the girls squealed and everything else when the bang went. It was an old gun of the Crimean war days, they used to have a whole battery of them. And - other times we used to go up
 
there if there was any big parade of the - of the garrison, like a review. I have been up there when - King Edward was there, to and Queen Alexandra reviewing the troops, which was always of course a great - affair because - the troops, even on Sundays, w
ere all in their coloured uniforms and not the - nondescript khaki we had to wear afterwards. And - sometimes I've been up there and after the parade's all over I've gone into the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 barracks}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and - well I knew various people, most of our friends were military 
people, either ex or in it, and perhaps I've gone up the barrack room and stopped there for dinner. I've ate many a meal in the - in the - of course, you could walk round the barracks then without let or hindrance. And - it used to be the thing if you had
 visitors you always took them up to the parade. To the gun. And then you always took them through the barracks, because the barracks were - especially in the mounted regiments, the artillery and etc., the stables were on the ground floor and then the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
' barrack rooms were on - above them you see, and they'd have their meals there, you'd see the - the men going down to the cook house to the long - and coming out with a long tray with all the - meals - the meals of all the men in that particular barrack 
room.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Could they fetch extra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well, no, they used to - somebody didn't turn up you see and somebody'd gone off out perhaps and - so they had one meal over and I used to - pass it over you see. Oh yes, used to often do that. Now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Just you, not your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were they just friends though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well people that I - we - I knew through the family you see. But not you can't even get in those barracks. As a matter of fact they don't - don't exist now, they've been pulle
d down. Oh yes, you often used to do that. Watch the horses being fed and groomed and that sort of thing. Even in the daytime as schoolboys - in holidays I often used to go up there and watch them. And as a matter of fact it was in the - it was through th
a
t that I - I had my first taste of the Army, that was the Christmas of - 1914. I did go with my father them because we - we went to the sergeants mess, in a tent, with a battery that had been called up and - we had various - refreshment, and they wanted u
s
, both father and myself to stay to dinner bit of course - that would have been terrible. So any rate the only way he got out of it, I got left behind to stay - as guest in the sergeants mess, guest of the battery sergeant major. Well the only refreshment
 
they had for me was port. And they kept me there until quite late in the evening when we got home. And - well I don't mind telling you I was pretty squiffy. Much to mother's disgust. Any way I sort of went to bed - I fell asleep on the couch as a matter o
f
 fact, and they left me there. I woke up in the morning feeling like nothing on earth and - of course boylike I'd sort of got in the back of my mind somebody had said once if you got in that state a hair of the dog that bit you - I saw a decanter of port,
 
so I had a swig, when they came down to breakfast they found me lying on the hearthrug clasping - clasping the decanter of port, the port had run all over the hearthrug. I was dead. That was my first introduction to the Army life. But anyway that's my - t
hat's not - oh no, it's - Army way - really the whole of Woolwich was - bound up with the Army really. Everything that the Army - anything that happened in the Army affected Woolwich you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did any other churches have parades, not military, but people parading outside, walking up and down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh yes. Most churches - after you came out of church you'd always find - a number of people sort of standing on the pavement or in the church grounds having a chat. That was considered the thing, sort of thing
, you were - to be seen, especially the ladies, to be seen and - admired sort of thing or - you showed off your new dress or your new hat. Oh yes, that always happened - and - of course most of the chapels I suppose you can say their doors opened on to th
e pavement so consequently there was always gang gathering round the pavement you see. Oh yes, that was always, a considered thing. But of course it was nothing like the military parade which was a - a real military occasion.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your parents go to church or chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 
Not until later, when my mother - well, my mother would - often go - we did, I beg your pardon, occasionally go - to the garrison church, because it was a much more - lively church, our own parish church was a very ,very - low
 church, low church of England and it was most miserable place. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 I could tell you stories about that but I won't. And the garrison church was usually - much - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 brighter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 , because they often used to use the string orchestra of the Royal Artillery band to accom
pany - for the musical part of the service. And we often used to go there, we were allowed to go in for evening service, in the gallery or down in the church, and we often used to go up because it was not far from our house you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 As a boy you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 As a boy. I remember - one famous -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 We were talking about Sundays and religion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes, that's right. We've been talking about Sunday school haven't we? That's right, the - garrison church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You went to the evening services?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh 
yes, we always used to go to - evening service. And of course on - on occasions they were - a - sort of big services. For instance, one I greatly remember is the - the service at the time of the sinking of the Titanic in 1912. The whole church was packed,
 
it was a big church with a big gallery. The whole thing was packed and the - in the chancel they had the string portion of the Royal Artillery band, which was quite a well known orchestra really, they were accompanying the singing, and I remember when the
 
whole lot, including organ and drums, played the - Dead March in Saul, there wasn't a dry eye in the house - in the place. It was occasions like that that were more - I - more often than not used to go with my mother because - she didn't go very often bec
a
use of course she was so deaf, she couldn't hear it. But - on an occasion like that we always had to - take her up. Harvest Festivals another one. It sound rather strange for an Army, the Army to be having a Harvest Festival, but they used to - they used 
to have a most elaborate affair. The place used to be decorated up with the most - looking like a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 fruiterer's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 shop gone mad. Apart from that - of course morning service there was not - was really not open to the public, it was mostly all troops. As regards 
the ordinary parish church which wasn't far form my house, well I can't say that we ever went in it. Except to be - perhaps marriages, births a - baptisms and - well there weren't any funerals in the family so it didn't matter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 It was a very,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15017164  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 very - It was a very very - low church if you know what I mean. Frightfully}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  low, very miserable place, it was a very dark place surrounded by a tall high trees so that the sunlight never got at it, it really was a cold - even on a summers day it was a cold miserable pl
ace. And consequently we used to avoid it like the plague. I think the last time I was in there was when I was married. And even then I didn't enjoy it, but that's another story. Because that's much more recent. As for - as regards the rest of Sundays, we
l
l - Sunday evenings of course we usually went out with father and mother, the whole family, my two sisters and myself and father and mother. We'd - perhaps walk over what is called Plumstead Common - we'd - youngsters would play about on the way of course
,
 but usually we had to decorously - walk in front. Sometimes we'd go across the river to North Woolwich. We'd go over on the free ferry, that was quite an exciting time for us youngsters. And - listen to the band in a park over there. Another one we used 
t
o do was another sort of walk across the common and up; into a wood, which is called Boston Woods on the - sort of slopes of Shooters Hill coming down to the river, where there'd be another band in a bandstand. Those usually used to be the - well the summ
e
r - Sunday evenings. The winter - Sunday evenings one was usually at home unless it happened to be a fine evening and then perhaps I might go out with my father and as I said we'd usually go down to the market place and - listen to the various brands of p
olitical wisdom, shouted at one another from - various groups. Apart from that there was really Sunday was a very - a sort of tame day.
