\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 How often would you go to this evening service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well - I suppose - taking my mother would be - five or six ti
mes a year. Myself, it was not a regular - thing, we were not - regular church people or anything - and as youngsters of course having had an after - solid afternoon of - Sunday school we felt we'd had enough. So that - it was not a - a regular thing but 
o
f course amongst - quite a lot of people it was regular thing to go to - church or chapel. Very often I think in lots of ways possibly - to be seen, because you came out of church there was always usually groups on the pavement outside having a little cha
t and - whether they were discussing - somebody's hat or something of that as is usually said I don't know, but - I know there used to be but - it was not very often we went - did go - go to church really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You didn't have family prayers in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What about grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Quite frankly I can't remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Your parents really hadn't much to do with the church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They hadn't, no. No. I don't think father'd - after he left the Army - ever went to church except
 on the sort of state occasions. Whether he had enough of it in the Army or not I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 It would just be your mother who went to this evening service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes. Mother and - father would never go. No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What time did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
In the weekdays usually about - about six. About six or half past. He usually, yes, he'd always come - six or half past, always, well unless he - I think they worked until - six at one time, and we were not far from the
 - from the Arsenal. Then I believe they altered afterwards to about half past five. I know I often used to go down to meet him and come home with him. And - he used to sometimes go down at - lunchtime and meet him and walk up with him, especially in scho
ol holidays. And one of the things I always remember then were the - while - whilst waiting for him outside the Arsenal gates - the boys - who were working in the Arsenal would come out to a neighbouring pub to get the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 workmen\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  beer, and they'd always have
 a long stick, a piece of timber about an inch square with a number of hooks all along it, and hanging on the hooks were tin cans, which was each mans beer can. And you'd see them - sometimes there were two of these cans carrying somewhere about - oh, abo
ut forty cans, twenty on each. It's a thing I've never seen - since the - well, since - fourteen - 1914, I think - I don't think they ever did it afterwards, because I - they had canteens in the - in the works then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They didn't have any food in the works then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no. No, no, there was no food in the works then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you boys go in to take food in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No, you could go down to the gate and - you could go down to the gate with say father's - dinner or - something of that sort. And he'd come ou
t of the gate and bet it you see, and they usually used to go perhaps into a neighbouring pub and sit there and eat it. The boys who came out for the beer often used to take things back, like pies and - things like that. But that was the only way of getti
ng food unless you took it in yourself. There was no canteens or anything of that sort in those days.
