, \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 And then perhaps all the way up South Kensington. To one of the museums. I'd have a - some packet of - sandwiches or something or other in my pocket. And - I used to thoroughly enjoy the walk - and walk all the way home. At that time it was th
e only way I could do it because I had no money sort of thing. But - afterwards we used to sometimes - go up to London - on an outing - on what was called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 workman\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  train, when you could then get up to London for fourpence return. I - that was a specia
l - thing by act of Parliament laid down when they first opened railways I believe. But - I know that fare now is somewhere about - three or four shillings. But even then we used to go up - I used to go up then, sometimes with my father if - he was on hol
i
day, but not very often, it was more often than not I used to wander up - there looking at all the funny little shops and - curious little shops and - that sort of thing on the way up and dawdle along and thoroughly enjoy myself. Oh it used to take long -
 long walks on my own. And into the countryside, yes, around about. Just - depending on - sort of how the spirit moved me sort of thing. Really. Yes, about twelve miles to Westminster Bridge. Oh I often used to do that
