Well no we didn't. We felt we were sort of - comfortable. But of course as I - sort of got on, round the twelve, thirteen, fourteen, I began to 
realize, that things were a bit - awkward, but mother was an excellent manager and she was a very saving person. And - so that we were never really - up against it. I mean at the end of the week, perhaps Friday it might be a - a bit of a - a scratched mea
ls and that sort of thing, but there was always a meal, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 If she'd had a much larger family it would have been different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh, if we'd had a much larger family, yes, there was only three of us, if we'd had a larger family it might have been
 - it might have been much tighter. It might have been much worse. Clothes for instance, we always had - decent clothes. Although - mother made - made a lot of them. And we always had to look after them. You see. And shoes, well father always mended them.
 
So that - we were never - like - quite a lot of families who possibly were in the same position financially, where the youngsters were running about with no shoes and stockings. The - shirt tails hanging out of their britches and that sort of thing. Which
 
- did occur. But then of course - in lots of - lots of areas of the town they were - it was a pretty poor area, and - it was very funny within the very poor area there were more pubs than there was - in the other areas. And consequently that may have cont
r
ibuted to the - to the poorness. In fact it did, there's no doubt about it. You see. It was all a case I think of peoples' - own - upbringing you see, my father and my mother - my father's mother died when he was about - sixteen. His father cleared off an
d
 left the family and my father - and his eldest sister practically brought the rest of the family up and there was - let me see - oh somewhere about eight of them. They both had to work - you see. And - my mother, well she was in service when she was four
teen, she went - off - to live with another aunt and uncle whom I'd never seen - in fact I can't even remember their names now, who lived at Whitstable, he was a fisherman.
