\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 on the blackboard and he had the blackboard away from us and he was behind it so he couldn't see the class. And I remember this boy suddenly - standing up in the classroom and holding up a stuffed monkey, and yelling out - boys, here's old Pon
go. And Pongo came round behind the board and said, and who is Pongo? Consequently of course there was a sixer. Another - teacher we had, it was the mathematics master if I remember rightly, he was a little short and very tubby man, his name was Mellor an
d of course he was always called Mouldy. Mouldy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 Mellor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 more than anything else. But - they were all quite - quite good teachers really. They were strict. And - but they were always - they were dedicated teachers and they - were - they would always - sort of
 acknowledge good work. I know one of my - I suppose my best subject was English, and I often used to find that in morning assembly before school started, the headmaster standing up and reading one of my - assays, to the whole school, much to my disgust b
e
cause I was always - leg pulled over it. But - and then of course we had - we had - other teachers, they mostly all had their own one subject. And - we had our sports teachers. But sports sessions were things I used to hate. I could never see the sense of
 
going up into a - cold winters afternoon on a muddy field chasing a - muddy ball up and down, or - cricket I never used to like either, although I love watching it. Swimming I used to hate - hate like poison, because - well I had been down for the third t
i
me once and I know the first swimming lesson somebody - pushed me in. And in going in - it was in the shallow end and I hit me head on the bottom. So I was dragged out then and after that I hated swimming lessons. And two other - lessons I used to detest 
w
ere - woodwork, because we used to have to go - we'd have a special classroom for woodwork - I don't think I ever succeeded in making anything except a very - very simple pipe rack I once took home to father, which he never used. And I don't blame him bec
a
use I thin the thing would have fallen to bits if he'd have put a pipe in it. I was never any good at that. And the other one was metal work. Metal work. Yes. We used to have to go to a school about a mile away for metal work. And - when you got there all
 
you had to do was sort of file a piece of - round bar iron into a square - which I always used to think was an awful waste of time because I could never see the sense of it. But - those things - at - at school itself, the arts side of it - history, geogra
phy, English, except parsing, I used to hate parsing and paraphrasing - which we used to have to do a lot of in those days.
