Oh yes, you had to have a register you see. Each - each master when he got his class into his room had to call the register and you had to answer your name. So that there was no - sort of dodging it, playing t
ruant, you were soon found out. I mean one day - if you were missing one day well you were expected to bring a note with you - the next day you turned up to explain why. Or if - you sort of - there was some reason why you couldn't come back after the lunc
h
 break - well you were supposed to bring a note in the morning from either mother or father to explain why. That was always strictly - stuck to, there was not much chance of - you could play hookey of course, but you were soon found out. And of course if 
y
ou did it too often you soon had the - school inspector or as - it's still called now - well at least it's what they call the attendance officer now, but we used to call, and I thin people do still use the term, the school - the school board man, would co
me round knocking at the door wanting to know why little Willie wasn't at - hadn't been to school you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You knew children who played truant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. There were some of them that used to. Oh yes. And then of course if it - if it became a littl
e bit too - too much of a good thing well father would be up at the local police court for - not a - his child not attending school. Oh yes, that - that happened quite - quite often. And I've known - I've known youngsters do it - used to play hookey as fa
r as that goes. But - I can't - I - I don't know that I ever did, I can't remember ever doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You went home for lunch - dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. Well I was only - only five minutes down the road you see. But we all went home for lunch. We all stopped 
school at twelve. And - went back at two, so that there was plenty of time even if you lived some distance away, of getting home for - lunch you see, but I was only just down the road, it was only - five minutes, or less than that if I ran. And - we - fin
ished school gain about half; past - half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did your mother ever come up to the school and meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. No. Parents very seldom came up to the school unless - you have some irate mother coming up - having a row about little Wil
lie having had a sixer across the bottom or something of that sort. And then it was merely - sort of - you used to get people who were a bit pugnacious, but - as regards - like they do now, parents and teachers - sort of working together, there was never 
a
nything of that. The only time I suppose parents would come to school - come to the school in the ordinary way would be prize giving. And even then sometimes they wouldn't come. It just depended. I can't remember - mother ever going - coming up to the sch
ool except - perhaps after we'd been away ill she might come up to explain to - the teacher why and - all that, you know, he's got to be - you've got to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 careful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  for a day or two and that sort of thing. But there was no - no educational connection between
 - between parents and teachers. Teachers were really sort of - really regarded as a class apart. Oh yes, they were always regarded as being sort of in the - the upper class to a certain extent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They didn't live round you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No. They usually lived
 further out - in more modern built houses and in - perhaps what we used to consider was the - was the more well -to-do part of the place you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 How large an area did the children come from, did the school draw any children from the rather poorer part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Yes, it was a mixed - mixed area it drew from. We had a mixed collection of - of children. They came from - foremen's children, shopkeepers' children, labourers' children and casual workers' children, they - we were all mixed up as regards social class.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you separate out in the playground?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
No, I don't think there was much - except - perhaps you'd get - one or two of them were a bit - dirty or something of that sort, you used to avoid them. But generally there was not much social dis
tinction in school. About the only social distinction was sometimes - if the - a school - we did have a sort of school health visitor at the time - a sort of affair - which was mostly to see that ones hair was clean, and - of course if somebody was sent h
ome - for having - nits in the hair - then you'd avoid them like the plague because you didn't want them yourself. That was the only thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were there gangs in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. You - you'd have gangs in the playground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 But that was a different sort of basis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Well yes, it was more - perhaps you'd get some fellows - boys that - were a bit rough in their play and that sort of thing - they'd gang up together and - have a game of - oh what the dickens did we used to call it, one man - boy
 used to stand against the wall and then you get about four - bent down, one - the first one with his head in the other boy's tummy and they'd all be - the other's be head down with their head against the other back - boy's behind and then the rest of the
m would come along and leapfrog onto the back and see how many you could get up there without the - the boys collapsing. You see. That was one game they - we played during }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14378793\charrsid15017164 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  whatsname. Sometimes you get a - a sort of scratch - football - game going. Other
s would just; sit about perhaps. Just talking or reading. Yes, you used to play all perhaps - you know, corner playing - Jackie Fivestones or something of that sort. You used to gather together according to your - inclinations more than - more than anythi
ng else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were there any links between those groups playing in the playground and those who would play outside later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Well it just depended whether - where the - the playground group lived in general. If they lived in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 same}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  street or two or thr
ee streets near at hand, they might - make a - a - play gang again. But if they were scattered all over the place well they wouldn't until they were back in the playground again you see. There was no gangs - as - you think of gangs at the present moment, 
g
oing round - getting up to mischief and - that sort of thing, I mean - you used to - perhaps a dozen of you be playing bout and you - might run down the road and as you passed the newsagents shop you'd - knock all his - billboards flat. But - that's about
 all the - or you might go along and in some - streets, the houses opened onto the pavement and the doors were sort of together. Well you very often - we'd often - of some of you would - tie the knockers together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Were there any groups of boys standing at the corner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Not at our age, you'd get them - the older age. Over the - over the fourteen, the boys - that had left school and had got - sort of - well jobs of some sort or other. You might find them - one or two of them but not very often, not a
s you get nowadays. You - in some areas you'd get them perhaps standing round talking. But not hanging around like we do now, and even then they never got into the - sort of vandalism and - mischief that they do nowadays. There was a - a - I think a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 great}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  deal more discipline - and of course there was more respect for the police. Because the police were about more. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 You}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 see, you always had a policeman patrolling - somewhere in your street. He'd always walk through your street two or three times a day but you
'd never know - what time of the day, you couldn't - sort of say, oh he'll be along at two o'clock and he'll be along at four. It was always - irregular times but there was always police about. And of course you had much more - respect for a policeman, or
 
- more respect for the law if you like. You regarded him not as a sort of public enemy number one as they do now. But more as a - as a friend really. Of course you used to get youngsters up to all sorts of games, I mean, youngsters would - pinch stuff off
 the stalls in the - in the market. Run along and grab an apple or something of that sort. But - it was done more for devilment really than it was done for - theft, with any - criminal instinct. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Do you remember street dancing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, I can't
 say that I do. Because of course - oh you - you get it - yes, I can. On a Bank Holiday you - in some of the areas - you'd get - perhaps dancing outside the pubs - on a Bank Holiday. It was when everybody had - sort of been having a - quite a number and t
h
ey would have got a bit - hilarious and they'd start - especially if the - if there was anybody about with the old barrel organ. Then you'd get - you'd get grown ups perhaps dancing. Of course, in the ordinary times you'd get - the barrel organ round, you
 
might get kiddies about trying to dance round. You got - often got that. But of course - the - the old barrel organ of course, you always got that around and sometimes the - the German band as the saying is, as they used to be called, which used to be qui
t
e - quite amusing. The - you'd get all these - about a dozen ladies - they really were mostly Germans as a matter of fact before 1914, they'd stand at the street come and play a few tunes. Very much umpah. But - they used to play music, and then of course
 
you would have the barrel organ which would - usually Italians brought those round, sometimes they'd have a monkey with them dressed up. The barrel organs usually played - the latest hit tunes from - the music hall or one of the - musical comedies, and - 
y
ou'd hear all the - messenger boys and that sort of thing going about their business, delivery boys on their bikes and all that sort of thing, would be whistling them. Everybody knew them. I mean, even the - the latest hit from say Flora Dora or - or the 
G
aiety Girl or something of that sort would always be - whistled by the delivery boys, it was quite the thing. And - and then of course you'd get the hurdy-gurdy man sometimes, again Italians. They - used to have a - a sort of box on a pole, which was - th
e
y used to wind a handle but it played by means of - a metal disc - which was rather like a pianola play - roll, but on a flat round disc. And it used to go over a cone, rather like a - some of the musical boxes you can see. And - they used to - used to pl
ay. Of course collecting money, ha'pennies and pennies usually thrown at them and that sort of thing. And consequently the streets used to be quite - quite gay as regards music really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Much more than now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes. 'h yes. I mean all you get now i
s - the sort of - well you used to get in the 1930's the - the - out of work Welsh miners - yell - singing - as they walked along, I always remember they used to in 1910, 1911 when there was a big crisis, there was a great deal of them out of work. They u
s
ed to come along then and - perhaps a procession of a - of a dozen of them - all out of work and of course there was no - out of work - benefit then. And - they used to come along singing - a very mournful lugubrious song - Oh what will - will - Oh what w
i
ll become of England, if things go on this day - something thousand working men are starving day by day. I always remember that bit of it. And it - it was the most mournful - song. But - then of course you'd always have the - the buskers as I mentioned be
f
ore. At the pubs. And at the - music hall and theatre queues. And some of them used to be - really - really good. It's marvellous how they used to stand up - especially the singers - stand up to - the sort of climatic conditions really and get the voice o
ver. Especially if you go - try to sing Bonny Mary of Argyll or something of that sort on the - and get it over the - the clatter and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 hubbub}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of a - of a crowded pub bar, it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 wants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 some doing, but they used to. Or they'd have a cornet. You can - you'd perhaps
 hear the cornet streets away sometimes. It was usually - it was usually a cornet or a - or a folding harmonium. Sometimes it was a concertina. Hut - the two most popular were the folding - the folding - harmonium and the - and the cornet. The folding har
monium was about as big as one of these little electric organs they sell in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 Woolworths}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
. I don't know whether you've seen them? I don't know how many octaves, they're only about that long, I don't know how many octaves there are but - they used to manage to 
get the tune out of them. Pedalling away like mad. Oh yes, you often got - especially Saturday nights would of course be - Saturdays and Sundays were the great days for them, but of course you used to get them out practically ever - in fact there were a l
o
t of people - I have had them pointed out to me when I was - when I was a boy in Woolwich - who's sole occupation it was. They used - that was their living. And they used to make quite a good living about of it. Doing nothing else but that, going round al
l the - all the pubs for a whole - a whole area, all the way round, in fact they were quite well known. Really. Not the sort of living I should have liked, rather precarious I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 You left school when you were twelve and a half?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 No, I left school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5244319\charrsid15017164 when}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  I was fourteen. In 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 So you really only had a few months in this job as an office boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 I - I - I got the office boys job - I left on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5244319\charrsid15017164 13th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of July, and I started work the following week. And I remained there until - the followin
g - January, 1915. No I didn't. Wait a minute, I'd left school at fourteen. I was fifteen and a half, no, I was there over a year. 1915 when I left. No, when did I join the Army? 1916, that's right, of course. Wait a minute. I always get muddled up in thi
s. No, wait a minute, I left - I left school in 1913, of course I did. I was fourteen in 1913. And it was 1915 I joined the Army. So I was there in that job all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Can you describe the office, what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh yes, it was the - an offi
ce partitioned off the end of a showroom and it was equipped with desks, with that - were - rather like the desks you see in the pictures portraying dickens - you know, high things with two slopes and a - ledger rack in between, and then high - high stool
s
 up about so high, used to be a - bit of a job sometimes for me to get up on them. And there were - spaces for four clerks, there were only two of us. The cashier - and - he was an old bachelor, and a most meticulous man. I remember him keepings there one
 
night - quite late - because in balancing up his day book - he - was a ha'penny out. And he wouldn't give up until he found that ha'penny. We all offered to put it in but he wouldn't have it. But he was always like that. Another occasion - he had a till y
o
u see - as a matter of fact in this firm it was a furniture dealers, and they did a lot of hire purchase work and of course in the office it was a case of people coming in - Saturday - Friday nights, Saturdays, all day Saturday paying their weekly install
m
ents, so there was always quite a bit of - money taken you see. And - he used to take them through a window and his till was one of the old fashioned - ball tills. And of course if you pushed the drawer in too far - hard, sometimes the money would shoot o
u
t one of the - one of the boards. And on one occasion there was an awful stink. He was a sovereign out and of course this was the days when - before notes, when actually gold was used. He was a sovereign out. And there was a most awful stink, I know every
body had to check everything through, and of course it was my job - as he entered up these - books, the peoples paying in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 books sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of thing and he'd enter it into his day book and then I had to transfer from his day book into the ledgers, the ledger accou
nts of each person. And then we had to check every one of these entries through - against one another. And we checked everything we could possibly thing of. And then somebody - oh I think it was the managing director was waiting to - waiting to lock up an
d go home. He came, he said, hell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5244319\charrsid15017164 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 he said, I'll give you the pound - oh - the old cashier wouldn't have it. And - he said, well, he said, have you pulled the drawer cut? So - oh - so the cashier said, no. He said, I will. And he pulled the drawer out and t
here was the sovereign lying in the bottom of the - tray. It had shot out as he pushed the in you see. But he was a most meticulous man, always used to say he - he hadn't blood in his veins, he'd only got red ink. He was that type of - dry as dust individ
u
al. Figures - and his cash book were absolutely his - whatsname. Another job I used to have to do was to make out the copies of the hire purchase agreements. The agreement would be made out and signed and sealed and all the rest of it, or signed over a si
x
penny stamp. And then I used to have to - make a copy - all on printed forms, I used to make the copy - so that it would be handed over to the - hiree. And then of course another job of mine was to always take all the - ledgers down to the safe which was 
down in the basement. And it was a bit of a job, put them in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 strong room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 - the safe and - pile of these blessed ledgers, they were thick, the - the covers were about a quarter of an inch thick and they were not of flimsy paper I can assure you. They wer
e thick and - were untearable paper actually. And they were very heavy and I used to - I used to grouse like made about it, in fact one night we did have a - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5244319\charrsid15017164 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  have an awful row about it. But - it was not a - a very - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 onerous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 - you know, I was never
 overworked sort of thing. The hours were long. It was nine in the morning until - six o'clock on most nights, Friday nights was - until - eight. And - I think on Saturday nights it was nearly - nearly ten before we finished, you see, the ordinary shop ho
u
rs. And of course we had Thursday afternoons off. And when I first started, I went to - went for this job, I got it entirely on my own, I saw the advertisement in the paper and I went to see them and I was taken on and I - my initial salary was seven and 
sixpence per week. I was there six months and when I got a rise of half a crown and I thought I was a millionaire. But - let me see, I don't think I was getting much more than that when I - when I really left.
