\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 What was this other clerk like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
Oh he was a - he was a - a young - he was married. He was a young fellow I suppose about thirty. He was married and - a bit of a bohemian. I remember he did - ask me to go to a party at his house one nigh
t. And - he lived near us, in a rather big house, and it was a - well, what I thought was at that time was quite bohemian. There was much - liquid floating about, and - much cuddling and canoodling round the place. I felt most horribly out of place and I 
d
on't mind telling you I didn't stop there very long. It was - rather reminds me - reminded me I suppose of quite a good description of it would be - one of the parties of - George Erosmith's - Mr Nobody, you know, I don't know whether you've ever read it 
-
 which is a very good picture of the period. It was sort of a - well - it was not quite a bachelor party because quite a number of the couples were married but - they didn't seem to be - particularly - what shall I say - I don't quite know how to put it -
 
it was rather a peculiar affair and I didn't stop for very long. But - well, I don't say they were quite that but they were flirting all over the place. After the war - I don't know, but I think he had - some German connections, because - after war broke 
o
ut in August '14 - he suddenly started - using German in the office, speaking - you know, using German places and phrases and that sort of thing. And it was through that that - I - sort - I sort of joined the Army because as I say, he got my goat one day 
a
nd I flung a ledger at him. I didn't hit him unfortunately, but - he annoyed me so much that I - I did, I lost my temper and threw this at him. And - what happened to him afterwards I don't know. I've never - never heard of the man, I daresay he was calle
d
 up and - he might have been killed for all I know. There you see, I didn't go back - to Woolwich after I - after I joined the Army, except for just - a few days. Until - I was a few days in 1918, then I left again and I didn't go back for 19 - after - 19
1
9 was the next time I went back, and then I wasn't back in England - well, I wasn't in Woolwich much because I was in Aldershot, I was there for bout six months and then I was out. And I didn't come back again until 1928. So that really that part of - of 
l
ife is - a sort of - I often say, a sort of lost generation really. Because all - when I came back all the people that I knew - and - sort of scattered all over the place, those people I used to go to school with - were married and were fathers and that s
ort of thing and I knew nobody. In fact it wasn't until the second world war in the Home Guard one day - I - was signals officer for the local battalion for a while, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 lieutenant}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of the Home Guard came up to me and - made some remark to me which sounded rather - suspicious, I wondered what he was getting at. And - I asked him }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5244319\charrsid15017164 after }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
another remark which - rang a bell somewhere and I suddenly discovered that this - this man was - a boy I knew at school and I'd never seen him since I left school.
