\insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 course slang}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 was used amongst the - amongst the - the staff or - describing customers wand that sort of thing but then it was the ordinary common slang of the str
eets really. I can't remember any - particular - trade - term alone, except that one, the spivs - the spivs. That's the only one I can remember of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 They didn't use back slang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Oh no, you only got back slang amongst the - amongst the - coste
rs - the costermongers, the stall holders and the - in the square, in the market, and - people of that nature. They were always called - regarded as being very common, and used to get a lot of back slang amongst them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 You'd get it in some of the shops in that area too. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
For instance, you'd get of course the apples and pears and all the rest of it which is quite well known, or - after - 1914 of course if you wanted to be - derogatory of somebody you might - might say he was an ablag}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164  (?)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 . Yes. That being German. But you can put it round the wrong way so that it wouldn't too }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 
obvious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  and you wouldn't get a punch on the nose sort of thing. But - back slang - quite frankly you know you would hear a lot about back slang but - I can't say that - apart from the - apar
t from the stallholders in the market - and - people saying something for a joke - I can't - I can't - sort of recall that it was a general way of speaking. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 
The costermongers would use it if they were calling out their wares, they'd - call out all sorts of things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
And in fact sometimes it - it wasn't back slang, it was - real language but - they used to be noted for that, in fact there was one dear lady, and I think she's still living in Woolwich, or at least she was a little while ago, who always sold bana
nas and she was well known for - she used to say some of the most - outrageous things you could possibly - think of. I mean, it puts Hair and Oh Calcutta into a - into the shades now. She used to come out with when she was selling her bananas. And of cour
s
e you get some of the other - stallholders, the china people and that sort of thing, 'cos a lot of them would travel, they'd travel round to all these markets - and you'd get the man who'd - and I've seen it done quite often - who'd get a - a whole - fort
y
 piece tea set on - laid out on his arm and chuck it up in the air and catch the whole lot without braking anything. And - or a - a big dinner service, he'd do the same thing. Well I daresay you've seen it haven't you? I have many a time. Get it all laid 
o
ut on a - on the big meat dish, see the whole lot piled up and - throw the whole lot up in the air and catch it. No breakage whatever. Of course it was done as an attraction to attract people round and then they'd - then you see the - the - style of selli
n
g was they'd - auction it downwards. And - of course the thing was to - wait and see 'til he got it down as low as you could possibly - you could possibly get it before you shouted. Then of course he sold one at that price, then he'd start selling the oth
ers at the same price you see. You always did that, and the - fruit and that sort of thing, well there were always - apples and pears and that sort of thing that they've very often bring in a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 bit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  of backslang to - wake the - sort of - attraction. But it was
 not - I don't think you can call it - at least not in our time - can you call it a - a method of - a way of - of conversation or of even speaking really. Although - it was used of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 
You might get the - music hall people and that sort of thing perhaps use it but - to even them it was - it was really I think a - a - a - survival of something very, very much earlier. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
When - say - early - early 19th }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 century}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 I think really, when there were - a greater - sort of - criminal class sort of thing. When it was 
necessary for them to be able to speak - or convey something to somebody without the rest of the world knowing what you were talking about. I think it dates - I think it's a survival more of - of the Dickens period than anything else. Or perhaps earlier t
han that.
