Oh no. No. No, no. No, no. It was - really the - there were of course articles - if - I mean in the - in some - clerical jobs like accountants and that sort of thing, very - more professionals. But the ordinary clerk there was no - appr
enticeship. No, you just - got a job and that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13179849 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Did you feel that having a job changed your situation at home, your relationship with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12126379 CV  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 Yes, I suppose it did really. I mean I was a little bit more perhaps independent. And I wa
s able - sort of - I was able to assist - with the housekeeping and have a - shilling or two in my pocket, not that I had very much, but I remember I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid792229\charrsid15017164  feel quite the - the lad, especially as I - I haven't been in the job very long because of the - I got
 my first - real suit, long trousers and all the rest of it and I've got a photograph of that somewhere - in the house, I always remember the said suit because it was a lovely - cigar brown, and I had a brown felt hat - kid gloves, silver top cane, brown 
s
hoes. And I felt the absolute - real - sort of - Burlington Bertie sort of thing. I always remember that suit because - I wore it first on a Bank Holiday, and I went out on my own, complete with kid gloves and cane and all the rest of it, and I walked to 
a fair at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10750940\charrsid15017164 Bostall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid792229\charrsid15017164 
 Heath. And whilst in the middle of a fair I had - dropped my gloves, I bent down to pick it up - and as I did so every button on my trousers came off. So I had to walk home with my cane tucked under my arm, my hands in my trousers pockets,
 to keep the trousers up. And the funny part about it was, all the way home - of course I kept meeting people who knew me, and as it was a case then the rigour of raising one's hat, it became very awkward. I always remember that one. And I've got a photog
r
aph somewhere about the house of me in that suit - that I had taken - at the sort of local photographers, which was - of course quite a thing. But it did give me a certain amount of - more freedom, sort of thing, I could go out - on my own without - sort 
of - explaining where I was going or - getting permission and that sort of thing, and I could go to - the cinema. Without - sort of - explaining. I wasn't - still wasn't allowed to stop out late.
